// V2.4.1 accuracy corrections. Keyed by day_number.
// Each entry: { s: "What Happens Today", t: "Think About" }
// Applied by applyCorrections.js, updates ONLY summary + think_about_question.
module.exports = {
  // --- Patriarchs ---
  13: { s: "Abraham dies in a good old age and the covenant passes to Isaac. Rebekah gives birth to twins, Esau and Jacob, who struggle even in the womb, and Esau carelessly trades his birthright to Jacob for a bowl of stew. Isaac later reaffirms God's promises as he digs wells and makes peace in the land. Meanwhile Job's friends press him and he longs for an advocate before God.", t: "Esau gave away his birthright for a moment's hunger. What lasting gift of God might you be tempted to trade for something that satisfies only for a moment?" },
  14: { s: "Prompted by Rebekah, Jacob deceives his blind father Isaac and seizes the blessing meant for Esau, then must flee his brother's anger. On the way he sleeps at Bethel and dreams of a ladder reaching to heaven, where God renews the covenant promise to him. Job and his friends continue their painful debate over the meaning of suffering.", t: "At Bethel God met Jacob in the middle of his running and fear. Where might God be meeting you in an unsettled or in-between season of life?" },
  15: { s: "Jacob arrives in Haran and falls in love with Rachel, but Laban tricks him into first marrying Leah, and he labors many years for the wives he loves. Through Leah, Rachel, and their maidservants, the sons who will become the tribes of Israel are born. In Job, Job clings to hope, declaring, 'I know that my Redeemer lives.'", t: "Even in his suffering Job dared to say, 'I know that my Redeemer lives.' Where do you need to hold on to hope in God when circumstances feel against you?" },
  16: { s: "After years of tension, Jacob slips away from Laban with his family, and the two men finally make a covenant of peace. Returning to face Esau, Jacob spends the night wrestling with a mysterious man until daybreak and is given a new name, Israel, 'one who strives with God.' Job and his friends keep wrestling with why the righteous suffer.", t: "Jacob wrestled with God through the night and would not let go without a blessing. What are you wrestling with God about right now, and can you keep holding on to him in it?" },
  17: { s: "Jacob and Esau meet again, and the reunion Jacob dreaded becomes an embrace of forgiveness. But peace is shattered when Jacob's daughter Dinah is violated and her brothers Simeon and Levi take violent revenge on the men of Shechem. Job continues to long for an audience with God to plead his case.", t: "Jacob braced for revenge but received his brother's embrace. Is there a broken relationship where God may be inviting you to take the first step toward reconciliation?" },
  18: { s: "God calls Jacob back to Bethel to renew the covenant, but the journey is marked by loss: Rachel dies giving birth to Benjamin, and Isaac is laid to rest by his sons. The line of Esau is recorded as the nations of Edom. Job marvels at God's majesty even as his friends question his integrity.", t: "Jacob's return to God was woven through both blessing and grief. How might God be present to you in a season that holds joy and sorrow together?" },
  20: { s: "The story pauses on Judah, whose dealings with his daughter-in-law Tamar expose his failures, yet through this unlikely line God preserves the family from which the Messiah will come. Tamar's boldness secures the future when Judah will not. In Job, Job recalls happier days and laments how far he has fallen.", t: "God wove his saving plan even through this flawed and messy family story. Where do you need to trust that God can bring good out of the broken parts of your own history?" },
  21: { s: "Sold into Egypt, Joseph serves Potiphar faithfully and refuses the advances of his master's wife, choosing integrity even when it lands him in prison. There God remains with him, and he interprets the dreams of Pharaoh's cupbearer and baker. Job protests his innocence and longs for God to answer.", t: "Joseph chose to honor God even when doing right cost him his freedom. Where is God asking you to do the right thing, even if no one notices or it brings no reward?" },
  22: { s: "Joseph interprets Pharaoh's dreams of coming famine and is raised from prison to govern all Egypt, storing grain to save many lives. When famine strikes Canaan, his brothers come for food and bow before the brother they betrayed, not recognizing him. The Lord's hidden providence is quietly unfolding.", t: "Years of waiting in prison prepared Joseph for the moment God would use him. How might God be using a long or hidden season to prepare you for something you cannot yet see?" },
  23: { s: "The brothers return to Egypt with Benjamin, and Joseph tests their hearts by hiding his silver cup in Benjamin's sack. When Benjamin is accused, Judah, who once sold Joseph, now offers himself in his brother's place. Their change of heart prepares the way for reconciliation. Job continues to await God's reply.", t: "Judah, who once betrayed a brother, now offers his own life to protect one. Where is God inviting you to grow from past failures into genuine self-giving love?" },
  25: { s: "Jacob and his family settle in the land of Goshen as the famine deepens, and Joseph wisely provides for both his family and all Egypt. The aging Jacob blesses Joseph's sons Ephraim and Manasseh, crossing his hands to give the greater blessing to the younger. In Job, God himself begins to answer out of the whirlwind, pointing to the wonders of creation.", t: "God answered Job not with explanations but with the vastness of his creation. When you cannot understand your circumstances, can you still trust the greatness and wisdom of God?" },
  26: { s: "Gathering his sons, Jacob blesses each one and foretells their futures, promising that the scepter will not depart from Judah. After Jacob's death, Joseph reassures his fearful brothers with words of grace: 'You meant evil against me, but God meant it for good.' The book of Job ends as Job repents before God and is restored.", t: "Joseph told his brothers, 'You meant evil, but God meant it for good.' Is there a past hurt you can begin to entrust to God, believing he can bring good even from it?" },

  // --- Egypt and Exodus ---
  29: { s: "God sends Moses back to Egypt with signs to perform, patiently answering his hesitations and excuses. With Aaron at his side, Moses first confronts Pharaoh, who responds by crushing the Israelites with heavier labor, bricks without straw. In Leviticus we begin to see how God provides the sin offering to restore his people when they fall.", t: "Moses offered God one excuse after another, yet God still called and equipped him. What hesitation or sense of inadequacy is God gently inviting you to bring to him?" },
  30: { s: "God reassures Moses, renewing his promise to deliver Israel and make them his own people. The contest with Pharaoh begins as Aaron's staff becomes a serpent and the Nile is turned to blood, the first of the great plagues. Leviticus continues with the guilt offering, showing God's desire to make wrongs right.", t: "God answered Israel's discouragement by reminding them whose they were. When you feel weighed down, how does it help to remember that you belong to God?" },
  31: { s: "The plagues continue as frogs, gnats, and swarms of flies fall upon Egypt, while Pharaoh's heart hardens with each refusal to let Israel go. God begins to set his people apart, sparing the land of Goshen. Leviticus details the offerings, showing that worship is to be given God's way, not our own.", t: "Pharaoh hardened his heart again and again against God's clear signs. Is there an area where God has been speaking clearly and you have been slow to respond?" },
  32: { s: "God sends plagues on Egypt's livestock, then boils, then a devastating hail, yet still Pharaoh will not relent. Even as judgment falls, God makes a way of protection for those who heed his word. Leviticus continues the law of the offerings, teaching reverence in approaching a holy God.", t: "Some Egyptians who feared the Lord's word brought their servants to safety before the hail. When God warns or prompts you, how readily do you act on it?" },
  33: { s: "Locusts strip the land and a thick darkness covers Egypt, and God announces the final and most terrible plague, the death of the firstborn. The long struggle with Pharaoh nears its climax. In Leviticus, Aaron and his sons are ordained as priests, set apart to stand between God and his people.", t: "Pharaoh kept bargaining with God rather than fully obeying him. Where might you be offering God a partial 'yes' when he is asking for your whole heart?" },
  36: { s: "Having passed through the Red Sea, Israel bursts into the Song of Moses and Miriam, praising God their deliverer. But the joy soon gives way to grumbling over bitter water and hunger, and God answers by sending manna from heaven each morning. Leviticus teaches Israel to distinguish clean from unclean as a holy people.", t: "God gave manna only one day at a time, teaching Israel to depend on him daily. Where is God inviting you to trust him for today rather than worrying about tomorrow?" },
  37: { s: "When the people thirst, God brings water from the rock at Moses' command, and Israel prevails over Amalek while Moses' hands are held up in prayer. His father-in-law Jethro then advises him to share the burden of leadership by appointing trustworthy judges. Leviticus continues its teaching on purity and new life.", t: "Israel prevailed as long as Moses' hands were lifted, and others held them up when he grew tired. Who helps hold up your arms in prayer, and whose might you help hold up today?" },
  39: { s: "God gives Israel laws for ordinary life, how to treat servants, settle disputes, and make restitution, so that justice and mercy shape the new nation. These ordinances flow from the God who has just redeemed them. In Leviticus we read of the cleansing of those healed of disease, a sign of God's desire to restore his people to community.", t: "God cared about the smallest details of how his people treated one another. How might God be asking you to bring more justice and mercy into your everyday dealings?" },
  40: { s: "The law continues with God's special concern for the vulnerable, the widow, the orphan, the poor, and the stranger, warning Israel not to oppress those without protection. To care for the weak is to honor the God who heard Israel's own cry in slavery. Leviticus teaches that even ordinary life is lived before a holy God.", t: "God told Israel to remember they were once strangers and so to care for the vulnerable. Who are the overlooked people God may be asking you to notice and care for?" },
  41: { s: "God gives laws for the Sabbath, the sabbatical year, and the great feasts, calling Israel to a rhythm of rest, justice, and worship, and promises to send his angel ahead to guard them. In Leviticus, the Day of Atonement is established, when the people's sins are carried away and they are reconciled to God.", t: "The Day of Atonement assured Israel that their sins could be wholly taken away. How does it move you to know that God longs to cleanse and reconcile you to himself?" },
  42: { s: "Moses reads the covenant to the people, who promise, 'All that the Lord has spoken we will do,' and it is sealed with sacrificial blood. Then Moses ascends the mountain into the glory of God. Leviticus underscores the holiness of blood and calls Israel to a way of life set apart from the nations.", t: "Israel sealed their 'yes' to God with a solemn covenant. What would it look like for you to renew your own wholehearted 'yes' to the Lord today?" },
  43: { s: "God gives detailed instructions for the ark, the table, and the lampstand, and for the tabernacle where he will dwell among his people, every detail pointing to the reverence due to his presence. Leviticus reaches its heart in the call, 'You shall love your neighbor as yourself,' and 'You shall be holy, for I the Lord your God am holy.'", t: "God's command to 'love your neighbor as yourself' stands at the centre of his law. Who is the neighbor God is placing before you to love concretely this week?" },
  44: { s: "Instructions continue for the altar, the courtyard, and the sacred garments of the priests, who will represent the people before God. Everything is ordered toward worship offered with reverence and beauty. Leviticus sets out the seriousness of holiness, that Israel might reflect the God who has set them apart.", t: "The priests wore the names of the tribes on their hearts as they came before God. Whose names do you carry on your heart before God in prayer?" },
  45: { s: "God describes the consecration of Aaron and his sons, set apart through sacrifice to serve as priests, and promises, 'I will dwell among the people of Israel, and will be their God.' The longing of the whole story is that God might live among his people. Leviticus continues with the holiness required of those who serve at the altar.", t: "The whole purpose of the tabernacle was that God might dwell among his people. How aware are you that God desires to make his home with you?" },
  46: { s: "God completes the tabernacle instructions with the altar of incense, the anointing oil, and the bronze basin, and fills the craftsmen Bezalel and Oholiab with his Spirit for the work. He again commands the Sabbath as a sign of the covenant. Leviticus continues to guard the holiness of what is offered to God.", t: "God filled ordinary craftsmen with his Spirit to do beautiful work for him. How might God want to use the skills and work of your own hands for his glory?" },
  47: { s: "While Moses is on the mountain, the people grow impatient and make a golden calf to worship, breaking the covenant they had just sworn. God's anger burns, but Moses pleads for the people and intercedes on their behalf. Leviticus, by contrast, lays out the sacred feasts that keep Israel turned toward the true God.", t: "Waiting on God, the people reached for an idol they could see and control. What 'golden calves' do you turn to when God feels distant or slow to act?" },
  48: { s: "Moses pleads to see God's glory, and the Lord passes by, proclaiming himself 'merciful and gracious, slow to anger, abounding in steadfast love.' The covenant is renewed, new tablets are given, and Moses' face shines from being in God's presence. Leviticus continues with the lamps, the bread, and reverence for God's name.", t: "God revealed himself to Moses first of all as merciful and gracious. Which of these names of God do you most need to trust in today?" },
  49: { s: "Moses gathers the people, who now bring freewill offerings so generously that they must be told to stop, and the work of building the tabernacle begins. Hearts once turned to an idol are now turned to glad, willing worship. Leviticus proclaims the sabbatical year and the Jubilee, God's plan for rest, release, and restoration.", t: "The people gave so freely that they had to be restrained from giving more. What would it look like for your giving to flow from a willing and joyful heart?" },
  50: { s: "The skilled workers craft the ark, the table, the lampstand, and the altar exactly as God commanded, and the tabernacle takes shape, each piece made with care for the dwelling place of God. Leviticus sets before Israel the blessings of faithfulness and the consequences of turning away, urging them to walk with God.", t: "The craftsmen made everything 'as the Lord had commanded,' down to the smallest detail. Where is God inviting you to a more careful, wholehearted obedience?" },
  51: { s: "The tabernacle is finished and set up, and the glory of the Lord descends and fills it so fully that even Moses cannot enter. God has come to dwell in the midst of his people, leading them by cloud and fire. Leviticus closes with vows and tithes, the response of hearts given wholly to God.", t: "When the work was complete, God's glory filled the tabernacle. As you offer your work and life to God, do you make room for his presence to fill it?" },

  // --- Desert Wanderings ---
  52: { s: "As Israel prepares to leave Sinai, God commands a census of all the men able to fight, organizing his people for the journey ahead. In Deuteronomy, Moses looks back over the long road from Horeb, recalling how fear once kept Israel from entering the promised land. A new generation now stands ready to move forward in faith.", t: "Israel's earlier fear cost them entry into the promised land. Where is fear holding you back from a step God is asking you to take?" },
  53: { s: "God arranges the tribes of Israel around the tabernacle, each in its place, so that his dwelling stands at the very centre of the camp. In Deuteronomy, Moses recounts the years of wandering and God's faithfulness in giving victory over hostile kings. God orders the life of his people around his presence.", t: "God placed his dwelling at the very centre of Israel's camp. What would it look like for God's presence to be at the centre of your life and home?" },
  54: { s: "The tribe of Levi is set apart for the service of the tabernacle, given to God in place of Israel's firstborn. In Deuteronomy, Moses recalls the defeat of Og and the settling of the eastern tribes, and learns that he himself will not cross into the land. God chooses and consecrates his ministers for sacred service.", t: "The Levites were given wholly to God for his service. What part of your life is God inviting you to set apart and consecrate to him?" },
  55: { s: "God assigns the Levites their duties in carrying and caring for the holy things of the tabernacle, each clan with its sacred task. In Deuteronomy, Moses urges Israel to keep the commandments and shun all idols, reminding them, 'The Lord is God; there is no other.' Faithfulness marks a people who belong to God.", t: "Moses pleaded with Israel to remember that the Lord alone is God. Is there anything competing with God for first place in your heart?" },
  56: { s: "God calls Israel to keep the camp pure, for he himself dwells among them. In Deuteronomy, Moses restates the Ten Commandments to the new generation and recalls the awesome day at Sinai when God spoke from the fire. The holy God invites his people to live in covenant with him.", t: "Moses reminded a new generation of the commandments their parents had received. Which of God's commands is he asking you to take to heart afresh today?" },
  58: { s: "The leaders of each tribe bring generous offerings for the dedication of the tabernacle, and God speaks to Moses from above the mercy seat. In Deuteronomy, Moses reminds Israel that they were chosen not for their greatness but because God loves them and keeps his promises. God draws near to a people he has freely chosen.", t: "God chose Israel not for their strength but simply because he loved them. How does it change you to know that God's love is a free gift, not something earned?" },
  59: { s: "Israel celebrates the Passover in the wilderness, and the cloud of God's presence settles over the tabernacle to guide their every move, when it lifts they travel, when it rests they stay. In Deuteronomy, Moses warns them to remember the Lord, for 'man does not live by bread alone.' God leads his people and feeds them with more than bread.", t: "Israel moved only when God's cloud moved, learning to follow his lead. Where do you need the patience to wait for God's direction rather than rushing ahead?" },
  60: { s: "At the sound of the silver trumpets, Israel sets out from Sinai for the first time, following the ark toward the promised land. In Deuteronomy, Moses warns them not to imagine their own righteousness has earned the land, recalling how quickly they made the golden calf. The journey forward is grounded in humility before God.", t: "Moses warned Israel against crediting God's gifts to their own goodness. Where might you need a more humble and grateful heart before the Lord?" },
  61: { s: "The people complain about the manna and crave meat, and God sends quail but also a plague, while seventy elders receive a share of God's Spirit to help Moses carry the burden of leadership. In Deuteronomy, Moses tells Israel what the Lord requires: to fear him, love him, and serve him with all their heart. Discontent and grace meet in the wilderness.", t: "Israel grumbled even after all God had done for them. Where might ingratitude be creeping in, and how could you cultivate thankfulness instead?" },
  62: { s: "Miriam and Aaron challenge Moses' authority and Miriam is struck with leprosy until Moses pleads for her healing. Then twelve spies explore Canaan, but ten return terrified, and only Caleb and Joshua trust God to give them the land. In Deuteronomy, Moses calls Israel to love and obey, setting before them blessing and curse.", t: "Ten spies saw giants; two saw the God who is greater than giants. When you face something daunting, do you measure it against your fears or against God's power?" },
  64: { s: "God gives Israel further laws for offerings and the Sabbath, and tassels to wear as reminders to keep his commandments. In Deuteronomy, Moses warns sternly against false prophets and every lure toward idolatry, calling Israel to cling to the Lord alone. God surrounds his people with reminders to stay faithful.", t: "God gave Israel tassels as daily reminders of his commandments. What simple reminders could help you keep God before you throughout your day?" },
  65: { s: "Korah, Dathan, and Abiram rise up against Moses and Aaron, and God's judgment falls as the earth opens and swallows the rebels. In Deuteronomy, Moses teaches the sabbatical year, the cancelling of debts, and the joyful pilgrim feasts. Human pride is set against God's call to mercy and worship.", t: "Korah grasped for an honor God had not given him. Where might envy or ambition be tempting you to grasp for what is not yours?" },
  66: { s: "To settle the dispute over the priesthood, God causes Aaron's staff alone to bud, blossom, and bear almonds, confirming his choice. In Deuteronomy, Moses gives instructions for future kings and priests and promises that God will one day raise up a prophet like himself. God confirms whom he calls to serve.", t: "God settled the matter not by argument but by bringing dead wood to life. Where do you need to let God, rather than your own striving, confirm your place and calling?" },
  67: { s: "God establishes the duties and provision of the priests and Levites, who receive no land but the Lord himself as their inheritance. In Deuteronomy, Moses appoints cities of refuge and gives laws for waging war with trust in God. Those who serve God find their security in him alone.", t: "The Levites' inheritance was not land but the Lord himself. What would it mean for you to say that God himself is enough for you?" },
  68: { s: "God gives the cleansing rite of the red heifer, and then at the waters of Meribah Moses strikes the rock in anger and is told he will not enter the promised land; Miriam and Aaron both die. In Deuteronomy, Moses continues to teach Israel laws of justice and compassion. Even faithful servants must reckon with their failings before a holy God.", t: "Even Moses faced consequences for a moment of disobedience. How can you receive God's correction with humility rather than excuses?" },
  69: { s: "When venomous serpents strike the grumbling people, God tells Moses to lift up a bronze serpent, and all who look to it in faith are healed, a sign that points ahead to the cross. Israel then triumphs over Sihon and Og. In Deuteronomy, Moses gives laws for honest and compassionate community life.", t: "Those who looked up to the lifted serpent were healed, foreshadowing looking to Christ on the cross. Where do you need to lift your eyes to the Lord for healing today?" },
  70: { s: "Fearful of Israel, King Balak hires the seer Balaam to curse them, but on the way Balaam's donkey sees the angel of the Lord and speaks to rebuke him. God will not allow his chosen people to be cursed. In Deuteronomy, Moses sets out laws governing who may belong to the Lord's assembly.", t: "God opened a donkey's mouth to get through to a stubborn prophet. How might God be trying to get your attention, perhaps through something unexpected?" },
  71: { s: "Again and again Balaam opens his mouth to curse Israel, but God turns his words into blessing, for no one can curse whom God has blessed. In Deuteronomy, Moses gives laws marked by justice, honesty, and mercy toward the poor and the weak. God's blessing over his people cannot be undone by their enemies.", t: "What others meant for cursing, God turned into blessing. Where do you need to trust that God can turn even opposition into good for you?" },
  72: { s: "Balaam foretells a star that will rise out of Jacob, a promise pointing toward the Messiah, yet Israel falls into idolatry and immorality at Peor until Phinehas' zeal turns away God's wrath. In Deuteronomy, Moses teaches Israel to bring their firstfruits with the confession, 'A wandering Aramean was my father.' Promise and peril travel together in the wilderness.", t: "Israel fell at Peor just as the promised land drew near. Where are you most tempted to let down your guard when things seem to be going well?" },
  73: { s: "A new census is taken of the generation born in the wilderness, those who will actually enter the promised land. In Deuteronomy, Moses commands that the blessings and curses of the covenant be proclaimed aloud from Mounts Gerizim and Ebal once they cross the Jordan. God prepares a new generation to take hold of his promise.", t: "A new generation was being prepared to receive what their parents had forfeited. What fresh start might God be offering you today?" },
  74: { s: "The daughters of Zelophehad receive a just inheritance, and God appoints Joshua to lead Israel after Moses. In Deuteronomy, Moses sets before the people the blessings that follow obedience and the curses that follow turning away. Leadership will pass on, but God's covenant endures.", t: "Moses set life and blessing, death and curse, plainly before the people. In the choices before you today, which path leads toward the life God offers?" },
  75: { s: "God details the offerings for Israel's feasts and the seriousness of vows made to him. In Deuteronomy, Moses gathers Israel to renew the covenant in the plains of Moab, binding this generation to the Lord. God invites his people into a relationship sealed by their faithful word.", t: "God took seriously the vows his people made to him. Are there promises to God or to others that you need to honor more faithfully?" },
  76: { s: "Israel wages war against Midian, whose seduction had led them into sin, and the spoils are divided. In Deuteronomy, Moses sets before the people a clear choice, 'I have set before you life and death; therefore choose life', and promises that God will restore them even after failure. The way of life is held open before God's people.", t: "Moses urged, 'Choose life.' What is one concrete choice today that would be choosing the life and love God offers?" },
  77: { s: "The tribes of Reuben and Gad ask to settle east of the Jordan and agree first to help their brothers win the land. In Deuteronomy, Moses commissions Joshua, writes down the law, and foretells that Israel will one day stray. As his life nears its end, Moses entrusts God's word to the generations to come.", t: "Moses made sure God's word would outlast him, written down for those who followed. What faith are you handing on to those who come after you?" },
  78: { s: "Moses records the long list of Israel's encampments, retracing every stage of the journey from Egypt to the edge of Canaan. In Deuteronomy, Moses sings his great Song, recounting God's faithfulness and Israel's waywardness as a witness for all time. Looking back reveals how faithfully God has led his people.", t: "Israel was called to remember every stage of the journey God brought them through. As you look back, where can you trace God's faithful hand in your own story?" },
  79: { s: "God marks out the boundaries of the promised land and names the leaders who will divide it among the tribes. In Deuteronomy, Moses blesses each of the tribes one by one before his death, entrusting them to the everlasting arms of God. The inheritance long promised is now within reach.", t: "Moses assured Israel that 'underneath are the everlasting arms.' Where do you most need to rest in the supporting arms of God right now?" },
  80: { s: "God appoints cities of refuge and secures the inheritance of Zelophehad's daughters as Israel's wilderness laws are completed. In Deuteronomy, Moses climbs Mount Nebo, sees the promised land from afar, and dies there, while Joshua takes up the leadership. A long era closes as God's promise stands ready to be fulfilled.", t: "Moses saw the promised land but was not to enter it himself, faithful to the very end. How can you remain faithful to God even when you may not see the fruit of your labors?" },

  // --- Conquest and Judges ---
  82: { s: "Israel renews the covenant at Gilgal, keeps the Passover, and Joshua meets the commander of the Lord's army. Then the walls of Jericho fall after Israel marches around them in obedient faith, but Achan's hidden sin brings defeat at Ai. Victory and failure both flow from how Israel responds to God.", t: "Jericho fell through obedience, but Achan's hidden sin brought defeat. Is there something hidden in your life that God is inviting you to bring into the light?" },
  83: { s: "After Achan's sin is dealt with, God gives Israel victory over Ai, and Joshua builds an altar and reads the law on Mount Ebal. Then the Gibeonites trick Israel into a treaty by pretending to come from far away, because Israel acted without consulting the Lord. Blessing follows obedience, and trouble follows presumption.", t: "Israel was deceived because they made a treaty without seeking God's counsel. Where do you need to bring a decision to God in prayer before acting on it?" },
  84: { s: "When five kings attack Gibeon, Joshua comes to its defense and God fights for Israel, even making the sun stand still until the victory is complete. The southern and northern campaigns sweep across the land as God hands the kings over to Israel. The Lord himself wins the battles for his people.", t: "Scripture says the Lord fought for Israel that day. Where do you need to trust that God is fighting for you in a battle that feels beyond your strength?" },
  85: { s: "The conquered kings are listed and the dividing of the land begins, with much still left to claim. Caleb, now eighty-five, asks for the hill country God promised him decades earlier, still ready to take it in faith. God keeps the promises he made long ago.", t: "Caleb held on to God's promise for decades and was still ready to act on it. What long-held hope is God calling you to keep trusting him for?" },
  86: { s: "The land is divided among the tribes by lot, each receiving its inheritance as God assigns, and the tabernacle is set up at Shiloh. The promise made to Abraham generations earlier is now becoming a settled reality. God faithfully gives his people a place to call home.", t: "Each tribe received its inheritance as a gift from God's hand. How might you receive your own circumstances and place in life as something entrusted to you by God?" },
  87: { s: "The remaining tribes receive their allotments, and Joshua himself is given a town as his inheritance. Cities of refuge and towns for the Levites are set apart, so that mercy and worship are woven into the life of the land. God provides for justice, refuge, and his own service among his people.", t: "God built places of refuge into the land so that mercy would always be near. Who might need to find a place of refuge and mercy in you?" },
  89: { s: "After Joshua's death, Israel fails to fully drive out the nations and falls into a cycle of forgetting God, suffering, crying out, and being rescued by the judges he raises up. Against this dark backdrop, Ruth the Moabite clings to her mother-in-law Naomi and to Naomi's God: 'Your people shall be my people, and your God my God.' Faithfulness shines amid faithlessness.", t: "Ruth chose loyal love when it would have been easier to walk away. Where is God inviting you to faithful love even when it costs you something?" },
  90: { s: "Israel cries out under oppression, and God raises up Deborah, a prophetess who leads with Barak to victory, while Jael strikes down the enemy commander Sisera. Deborah's song gives all the glory to God. Meanwhile Ruth gleans in the field of Boaz, who shows her kindness and protection.", t: "Boaz noticed Ruth, a poor foreigner, and treated her with generous kindness. Who around you is in need of being seen and treated with that same kindness?" },
  91: { s: "God calls the hesitant Gideon, reduces his army to just three hundred, and wins a stunning victory over Midian so that the glory belongs to God alone. Meanwhile Ruth boldly seeks Boaz as her kinsman-redeemer, trusting in his goodness. God works through the weak and the lowly to accomplish his purposes.", t: "God deliberately made Gideon's army small so the victory would clearly be his. Where might God be asking you to trust him precisely where you feel weak or outmatched?" },
  92: { s: "The era of the judges darkens through the ruthless Abimelech and the tragic vow of Jephthah, showing how far Israel drifts without God at the centre. Yet in Ruth, Boaz redeems Ruth and Naomi, and their son becomes the grandfather of King David. God quietly weaves the line of the Messiah through ordinary faithfulness.", t: "While the nation unraveled, God was quietly building the family of the Messiah through humble, faithful people. How might God be at work in the small, hidden faithfulness of your own life?" },
  93: { s: "Internal strife divides Israel as Jephthah clashes with Ephraim, and then God raises up Samson, set apart from birth, whose great strength is matched by reckless passions. His story begins to reveal both God's power and human weakness. God can work even through deeply flawed people.", t: "Samson was greatly gifted yet ruled by his impulses. Where might God be asking you to bring your strengths under the discipline of his will?" },
  94: { s: "Samson's strength is undone by his weakness as Delilah coaxes out his secret, yet in his final act, blind and humbled, he calls on God and brings down the temple of the Philistines. The book then turns to Micah's homemade idols and the wandering Danites, showing Israel's growing confusion. Even in failure, God's purposes are not defeated.", t: "Only when he was broken and blind did Samson finally turn back to God in prayer. Is God using a place of weakness to draw you back to himself?" },
  95: { s: "Judges ends in horror as a Levite's concubine is brutalized and Israel descends into civil war against the tribe of Benjamin. The refrain sounds the deepest problem: 'In those days there was no king in Israel; everyone did what was right in his own eyes.' The story cries out for a true and righteous king.", t: "When everyone did what was right in their own eyes, chaos followed. Where do you need to let God's truth, rather than your own preferences, guide your choices?" },
  97: { s: "In a time when God's word was rare, the boy Samuel hears the Lord call his name in the night and answers, 'Speak, for your servant hears.' Soon after, Israel presumptuously carries the ark into battle and it is captured, and old Eli dies; yet among the Philistines the idol Dagon falls before the ark of God. God raises up a faithful prophet and shows he will not be handled like an idol.", t: "Young Samuel answered, 'Speak, for your servant hears.' How might you make more space to listen for God's voice in the quiet of your day?" },
  98: { s: "The captured ark brings such trouble on the Philistines that they send it back, and under Samuel's leadership Israel repents and is delivered at Mizpah. But then the people demand a king like the other nations, rejecting God as their true king. Israel reaches for human security rather than trusting the Lord who has saved them.", t: "Israel wanted a king like everyone else instead of trusting God as their king. Where are you tempted to want what others have rather than trusting God's care for you?" },

  // --- Messianic Checkpoint (John) ---
  100: { s: "Jesus offers the Samaritan woman living water that wells up to eternal life, then heals an official's son and a man at the pool of Bethesda. Feeding five thousand from a few loaves, he declares, 'I am the bread of life,' the true food come down from heaven. Jesus reveals himself as the one who satisfies the deepest human hunger and thirst.", t: "Jesus promised the Samaritan woman water that would forever satisfy. What thirst in your own heart are you trying to fill, and how might you bring it to Jesus?" },
  101: { s: "At the Feast of Tabernacles, Jesus stirs division as some believe and others plot against him. He shows mercy to the woman caught in adultery, declares himself 'the light of the world,' and astonishes his hearers with the words, 'Before Abraham was, I am.' Then he opens the eyes of a man born blind, exposing the blindness of those who refuse to see.", t: "Jesus gave sight to a blind man while the seeing remained blind to him. Is there an area where you need Jesus to open your eyes to what you have been missing?" },
  102: { s: "Jesus declares himself the Good Shepherd who lays down his life for his sheep, then proves his power over death by raising Lazarus from the tomb. As the Passover nears, he is anointed at Bethany and enters Jerusalem to shouts of 'Hosanna.' The signs all point to who Jesus is and to the hour now drawing near.", t: "Jesus calls himself the Good Shepherd who knows his sheep by name. How does it comfort you to know that Jesus knows you personally and lays down his life for you?" },
  103: { s: "At the Last Supper Jesus kneels to wash his disciples' feet and gives them a new commandment: to love one another as he has loved them. He comforts them as 'the way, the truth, and the life,' promises the Holy Spirit, and calls them to abide in him as branches in the vine. Love and union with Christ are the heart of the new life he gives.", t: "Jesus said his followers would be known by their love for one another. Whom is Jesus asking you to love more deeply and humbly, even in lowly service?" },
  104: { s: "Jesus promises that the Holy Spirit will come and that their sorrow will turn to joy, then lifts his eyes to pray for his disciples and for all who will believe through them, that they may be one. In the garden he is betrayed and arrested, and Peter denies him as Jesus stands before the authorities. The hour of his self-offering has come.", t: "Jesus prayed for you by name when he asked that all his followers would be one. How does it move you to know that you were on Jesus' heart as he faced the cross?" },

  // --- Royal Kingdom ---
  106: { s: "Israel's demand for a king is answered as Samuel anoints Saul, a tall and humble young man searching for his father's lost donkeys. Saul is filled with God's Spirit and presented to the people as their first king. God grants Israel's request, even as the dangers of a king are set before them.", t: "Saul began humbly, surprised that God would choose him. As God entrusts you with responsibilities, how can you keep a humble heart before him?" },
  107: { s: "Saul rallies Israel to rescue the city of Jabesh-gilead, and his kingship is joyfully confirmed at Gilgal. Samuel then gives his farewell, calling the people to fear and serve the Lord and warning that both they and their king must remain faithful. A new chapter begins, hinging on obedience to God.", t: "Samuel urged Israel to serve the Lord faithfully with all their heart. What would wholehearted faithfulness to God look like in your life this week?" },
  108: { s: "Pressured and impatient, Saul oversteps by offering the sacrifice that was Samuel's to make, and Samuel warns that his kingdom will not endure. Meanwhile Saul's son Jonathan trusts God boldly, striking the Philistines convinced that 'nothing can hinder the Lord from saving by many or by few.' Faith and self-reliance stand side by side.", t: "Jonathan trusted that God can save 'by many or by few.' Where do you need to act in faith rather than waiting until everything feels safe and certain?" },
  109: { s: "Saul disobeys God's command in the battle against Amalek and is rejected as king, for 'to obey is better than sacrifice.' God then sends Samuel to anoint a shepherd boy, David, a man after his own heart, and David enters Saul's service. God looks past outward appearance to the heart.", t: "God reminded Samuel that he looks not on appearances but on the heart. If God sees your heart as it truly is, what is he inviting you to bring honestly to him?" },
  111: { s: "David's victories win him the people's love and a deep friendship with Jonathan, but Saul's jealousy festers into murderous rage. Twice Saul tries to kill David, and Michal helps him escape into the night. Envy begins to consume the king while God's hand protects David.", t: "Saul let jealousy of David poison his heart. When you notice envy rising over someone else's gifts or success, how can you bring it to God instead of feeding it?" },
  112: { s: "David and Jonathan make a covenant of loyal friendship, and Jonathan risks his father's anger to confirm that Saul truly means to kill David. With sorrow, the two friends part to protect David's life. Faithful love stands firm even when it is costly and dangerous.", t: "Jonathan stood by David even when it cost him his father's favor. Who has God placed in your life to love loyally, even when it is hard?" },
  113: { s: "Fleeing for his life, David receives bread and Goliath's sword from the priest Ahimelech at Nob, then escapes to Gath. But Saul, in his paranoia, has Doeg slaughter the priests of Nob, and only Abiathar survives. The cost of Saul's jealousy grows ever darker.", t: "David ran to the house of God in his time of need. Where do you turn first when you are afraid, and how might you run to God sooner?" },
  114: { s: "David rescues the town of Keilah from the Philistines, yet must keep fleeing as Saul relentlessly hunts him. Jonathan finds him in the wilderness and strengthens his hand in God. Even as a fugitive, David keeps seeking the Lord's guidance at every turn.", t: "Jonathan came to David in the wilderness and 'strengthened his hand in God.' Who can you encourage in God today, and who helps strengthen your own faith?" },
  115: { s: "Hidden in a cave, David has the chance to kill the sleeping Saul but refuses to lift his hand against the Lord's anointed, cutting only the corner of his robe. He calls out to Saul to show he means no harm, and Saul weeps. David leaves justice in God's hands rather than seizing it for himself.", t: "David spared his enemy and trusted God to judge rightly. Is there someone you are tempted to repay, whom God may be asking you to entrust to him instead?" },
  116: { s: "When the harsh and foolish Nabal insults David, David sets out for revenge, but Nabal's wise wife Abigail intervenes with humility and generosity, restraining David from bloodshed. He blesses God for sending her to keep him from sin. God uses a peacemaker to turn David from rash anger.", t: "Abigail's gentle wisdom kept David from a sin he would have regretted. When anger rises, are you willing to let a wise voice calm you before you act?" },
  117: { s: "Once more David comes upon Saul asleep and could end his pursuer's life, but again he spares him, taking only his spear and water jug as proof. He calls out across the valley, leaving Saul to answer to God. David's restraint reveals a heart that trusts the Lord's timing.", t: "Twice David refused to grasp by force what God had promised to give in time. Where are you tempted to force an outcome rather than wait on God?" },
  118: { s: "Weary of fleeing, David takes refuge among the Philistines, while Saul, abandoned by God, secretly consults a medium at Endor in his desperation. The contrast is stark: David still under God's protection, Saul groping in the dark. Saul's long turning from God reaches its tragic end.", t: "In fear, Saul sought answers anywhere but from the God he had abandoned. When you feel desperate, where do you seek guidance, and how can you turn back to God?" },
  119: { s: "David is sent away from the Philistine army, sparing him from fighting his own people, while Saul and his sons fall in battle on Mount Gilboa. The reign that began with such promise ends in defeat and death. An era closes as God prepares to raise up the king he has chosen.", t: "Saul's story ended far from where it began because of a heart that drifted from God. What small drift in your own life might God be inviting you to correct today?" },
  120: { s: "Instead of rejoicing, David mourns deeply for Saul and Jonathan, composing a lament for the fallen king and his beloved friend. In Chronicles, the genealogies begin all the way back at Adam, tracing God's faithfulness across the generations. David grieves with a generous heart, even for the one who hunted him.", t: "David grieved sincerely for the enemy who had sought his life. How might God be enlarging your heart to feel compassion even for those who have wronged you?" },
  121: { s: "David is anointed king over Judah, but a long struggle follows between his house and the remaining house of Saul. In Chronicles, the line of Judah is traced, the tribe from which the Messiah will come. God's chosen king takes the throne gradually, through patience and conflict.", t: "David became king only step by step, not all at once. Where is God asking you to be patient as his purposes unfold slowly in your life?" },
  122: { s: "Saul's commander Abner defects to David, seeking to unite the kingdom, but Joab murders him in revenge, and David publicly mourns, refusing to share in the bloodshed. Chronicles continues the genealogies of God's people. David shows that he will build his kingdom with justice, not treachery.", t: "David refused to profit from another man's violent act. Where might you be tempted to accept a wrong done on your behalf rather than standing for what is right?" },
  123: { s: "Saul's son Ishbosheth is murdered by men hoping to please David, but David condemns the crime and executes the killers, again refusing to let his throne be built on innocent blood. Chronicles records the lines of Levi and the priests who served God. David honors life even when a death would benefit him.", t: "David would not let evil be done in his name, even to his advantage. Is there a compromise you are tempted to accept simply because it would benefit you?" },
  124: { s: "All the tribes of Israel come together to make David king, and he captures Jerusalem, making it the city of David. In Chronicles, the genealogies continue, rooting the nation in God's faithful dealings. The promise of a united people under God's chosen king is finally realized.", t: "After long years of waiting, David received what God had promised. As you wait on God's promises, how can you keep trusting his perfect timing?" },
  125: { s: "David brings the ark of God to Jerusalem with rejoicing, dancing before the Lord with all his might. When David desires to build God a house, God instead promises to build David a house, an everlasting throne that points to Christ. God's covenant with David becomes a cornerstone of the hope of the Messiah.", t: "David wanted to give to God, and God responded with an even greater promise. Where might you discover that God's generosity far outruns anything you could offer him?" },
  126: { s: "David extends his kingdom through a series of victories, and the Lord gives him success wherever he goes. In Chronicles, we read again of Saul's death, David's anointing, and the mighty men who rallied to him. God establishes his chosen king and grants him rest from his enemies.", t: "Scripture says the Lord gave David victory wherever he went. How can you give God credit for the good that comes from your efforts, rather than claiming it as your own?" },
  127: { s: "Remembering his covenant with Jonathan, David seeks out Jonathan's crippled son Mephibosheth and welcomes him to eat at the king's table like one of his own sons. In Chronicles, the warriors who joined David are honored. David's kindness reflects the faithful, covenant love of God.", t: "David showed undeserved kindness to Mephibosheth for the sake of a promise. Who is someone you could show unexpected kindness to, simply out of love?" },
  128: { s: "When David's messengers of goodwill are humiliated by the Ammonites, war breaks out and God gives Israel the victory. In Chronicles, David's first attempt to bring the ark ends in tragedy when Uzzah touches it, teaching reverence for the holiness of God. David learns that God must be approached on his own terms.", t: "The ark could not be handled carelessly, for God is holy. How might you grow in reverence and awe in the way you approach God in prayer and worship?" },
  129: { s: "At the height of his power, David stays home from war, sees Bathsheba, commits adultery, and arranges the death of her husband Uriah to cover his sin. In Chronicles, by contrast, David brings the ark to Jerusalem rightly, with worship and joy. The greatest king reveals how even the faithful can fall.", t: "David's idleness and unchecked desire led him into grievous sin. Where do you need to guard your heart in the small moments before temptation grows?" },
  131: { s: "The consequences of David's sin ripple through his family as Amnon violates his sister Tamar and Absalom takes revenge, fracturing the household. In Chronicles, God reaffirms his covenant promise to establish David's throne forever. Even amid human brokenness, God's promise stands firm.", t: "David's private sins bore bitter fruit in his family. How do your choices, for good or ill, shape those closest to you?" },
  132: { s: "Through a wise woman's appeal arranged by Joab, the estranged Absalom is brought back to Jerusalem, though full reconciliation with David remains out of reach. In Chronicles, David's many victories are recounted. Wounds left unhealed in a family quietly prepare the way for greater sorrow.", t: "David allowed a half-hearted reconciliation that left wounds unhealed. Is there a relationship where God is calling you toward fuller, more honest reconciliation?" },
  133: { s: "Absalom wins the people's hearts and launches a rebellion, forcing David to flee Jerusalem in tears, even sending the ark back in trust that God will decide his fate. In Chronicles, Israel's wars and victories continue. Stripped of his throne, David clings to God rather than to his crown.", t: "In his lowest moment David surrendered his future to God's will. Can you entrust an uncertain outcome to God, trusting that he will deal kindly with you?" },
  134: { s: "As David flees, Shimei curses and stones him, yet David bears the insult humbly, leaving judgment to God. In Chronicles, David's prideful census brings a plague, and he repents, building an altar where the temple will one day stand. David accepts humbling correction and turns back to God.", t: "David received insult and correction without retaliating, trusting God to vindicate him. How do you respond when you are humbled or wrongly treated?" },
  135: { s: "God turns the cunning counsel of Ahithophel to folly, protecting David in his flight, while loyal friends risk everything for him. In Chronicles, David, denied the privilege of building the temple himself, gathers materials and charges Solomon to build it. David serves a future he will not see.", t: "David poured himself into preparing a work that another would complete. Where might God be asking you to labor faithfully for something whose fruit you may never see?" },
  136: { s: "David's forces defeat the rebels, but against his orders Absalom is killed, and the victorious king is overcome with grief for his lost son. In Chronicles, the Levites are organized for the service of God's house. Even in triumph, David's heart breaks for his child.", t: "David's love for his rebellious son endured even his betrayal. How does David's grief reflect the heart of God, who longs even for those who turn away from him?" },
  137: { s: "David is restored to his throne and shows mercy to those who had turned against him, choosing reconciliation over revenge as he returns to Jerusalem. In Chronicles, the priestly divisions are arranged for ordered worship. The restored king rules with grace toward his people.", t: "Returning in victory, David chose mercy rather than settling scores. When you are in a position of strength, do you lean toward grace or toward getting even?" },
  138: { s: "A man named Sheba leads another revolt, but the uprising is put down and the kingdom held together. In Chronicles, David appoints the musicians who will lead Israel's worship with song and praise. Even amid unrest, David centres his kingdom on the worship of God.", t: "David made the praise of God central to the life of his kingdom. What place does praise and thanksgiving hold in the rhythm of your own life?" },
  139: { s: "A famine and old debts of bloodshed are addressed, and David honors the bones of Saul and Jonathan, while his mighty men again defend Israel against the Philistine giants. In Chronicles, the gatekeepers are assigned their sacred duties. David attends both to justice and to faithful service before God.", t: "David honored the memory of Saul and Jonathan and saw that old wrongs were set right. Is there an old debt or unresolved matter God is asking you to make right?" },
  140: { s: "David sings a great song of deliverance, praising the Lord as his rock, fortress, and deliverer who rescued him from all his enemies. In Chronicles, the divisions of the army are organized for the kingdom's order. Looking back over his life, David gives all the glory to God.", t: "David called God his rock and fortress, his refuge in every trouble. When you look back over your life, where has God been your rock and deliverer?" },
  141: { s: "In his last words David proclaims that one who rules justly in the fear of God is like the light of morning, and his mighty men are honored. In Chronicles, David charges the assembly to build the temple and hands Solomon the plans, urging him to serve God with a whole heart. David passes on a vision rooted in the fear of the Lord.", t: "David urged Solomon to serve God 'with a whole heart and a willing mind.' What would it mean for you to serve God with both your whole heart and your full willingness?" },
  142: { s: "David's prideful census brings judgment, but when he repents God stays the plague at the threshing floor of Araunah, where David builds an altar, the future site of the temple. In Chronicles, David offers everything for God's house, Solomon is made king, and David dies after a long reign. The king's life ends in worship and surrender to God.", t: "David insisted on offering God a sacrifice that truly cost him something. What might it look like for your offering to God to be more than merely what is convenient?" },
  152: { s: "The Queen of Sheba travels far to test Solomon and is overwhelmed by his wisdom and the splendor of his kingdom, praising the God who set him on the throne. In Ecclesiastes, the Preacher weighs wisdom against folly and reflects on the limits of human understanding. Earthly glory shines, yet the search for lasting meaning continues.", t: "Even surrounded by wisdom and wealth, Ecclesiastes keeps asking what truly lasts. Where are you seeking lasting meaning, and how does it draw you toward God?" },
  153: { s: "Solomon's many foreign wives turn his heart toward other gods, and the kingdom that rose so gloriously begins to fracture as God raises up adversaries against him. In Ecclesiastes, the Preacher reaches his conclusion: 'Fear God and keep his commandments, for this is the whole duty of man.' Even the wisest king shows the danger of a divided heart.", t: "Solomon's heart was slowly drawn away by small compromises. Ecclesiastes urges, 'Remember your Creator', how can you keep your heart undivided toward God?" },

  // --- Messianic Checkpoint (Mark) ---
  155: { s: "Jesus appoints the twelve apostles to be with him and to be sent out, even as opponents accuse him and his own relatives misunderstand him. He teaches in parables, the sower, the growing seed, the mustard seed, showing how God's kingdom takes root and grows. Then, with a word, he calms a raging storm, leaving his disciples in awe of his power.", t: "The disciples asked, 'Who then is this, that even the wind and sea obey him?' When storms rise in your own life, do you trust that Jesus has power over them?" },
  156: { s: "Jesus frees a man tormented by demons, heals a woman who simply touches his cloak, and raises the daughter of Jairus from death. Yet in his hometown of Nazareth he is rejected, and he sends out the twelve to preach and heal. The chapter also recounts the death of John the Baptist and Jesus feeding five thousand from five loaves.", t: "A suffering woman reached out in faith, certain that even touching Jesus' cloak would heal her. With what need can you reach out to Jesus today, trusting his power and compassion?" },
  157: { s: "Jesus teaches that defilement comes not from outside but from the human heart, and he heals a Gentile woman's daughter and a deaf man. He feeds four thousand, then opens the eyes of a blind man. When Peter confesses him as the Christ, Jesus reveals that he must suffer, and calls his followers to take up their cross.", t: "Jesus said the heart is the source of what defiles us. What is stirring in your heart right now that you need to bring honestly to him?" },
  158: { s: "Jesus is transfigured in glory before Peter, James, and John, then heals a boy his disciples could not help. He teaches that the greatest must become the servant of all, welcomes children, and calls the rich to follow him. As he journeys toward Jerusalem, he foretells his death and heals blind Bartimaeus, who follows him on the way.", t: "Blind Bartimaeus cried out, 'Master, let me see again,' and would not be silenced. What do you most need to ask Jesus for, and will you keep asking?" },
  159: { s: "Jesus enters Jerusalem to shouts of 'Hosanna,' then cleanses the temple of those who made it a marketplace. He silences those who test him, tells the parable of the wicked tenants, and names the greatest commandment: to love God with all your heart and your neighbor as yourself. He praises a poor widow who gives all she has.", t: "Jesus noticed the widow who quietly gave everything she had. Does your giving to God flow from love and trust, or only from what you can easily spare?" },
  160: { s: "Jesus speaks of the trials to come and calls his followers to watchfulness. A woman anoints him for his burial, and at the Last Supper he gives his body and blood under bread and wine. In Gethsemane he prays in anguish, 'Not what I will, but what you will,' and is betrayed, arrested, and denied by Peter.", t: "In the garden Jesus prayed, 'Not what I will, but what you will.' Where is God inviting you to surrender your own will to his, even when it is hard?" },

  // --- Divided Kingdom ---
  162: { s: "After Solomon's death, his son Rehoboam threatens to rule even more harshly, and the ten northern tribes break away under Jeroboam, splitting the nation in two. To keep his people from worshiping in Jerusalem, Jeroboam sets up golden calves at Bethel and Dan. The united kingdom is torn apart, and Israel's long divided history begins.", t: "Rehoboam's pride and harsh words tore a kingdom apart. How might your words today either build others up or drive them away?" },
  163: { s: "A man of God boldly confronts Jeroboam's false altar, but is himself deceived and pays for his disobedience, a warning to heed God's word fully. In Chronicles, Rehoboam is humbled by an Egyptian invasion, and his son Abijah trusts God for victory over Israel. Faithfulness to God's word proves to be a matter of life and death.", t: "Even a true prophet fell when he listened to a voice contrary to God's clear command. How carefully do you weigh advice against what God has already made clear?" },
  164: { s: "God's judgment falls on Jeroboam's house for leading Israel into idolatry, and Rehoboam's reign ends in compromise. In Chronicles, King Asa of Judah tears down the idols, calls the people back to the Lord, and leads them in a wholehearted covenant. Two kingdoms, two directions: one drifting from God, one returning to him.", t: "Asa led his people to seek the Lord with all their heart. What would it look like for you to seek God wholeheartedly rather than half-heartedly?" },
  165: { s: "A rapid succession of kings rises and falls in Israel, most doing evil, until the wicked Ahab takes the throne and marries Jezebel. In Chronicles, Asa of Judah relies on a foreign alliance instead of God in his final years, while his son Jehoshaphat begins to walk faithfully. The contrast deepens between trusting God and trusting human power.", t: "In his last years Asa leaned on human strength rather than the God who had saved him before. Where are you tempted to rely on your own resources instead of trusting God?" },
  167: { s: "Worn down and afraid, Elijah meets God not in wind, earthquake, or fire, but in a gentle whisper, and is sent back to his mission and to call Elisha. In Chronicles, King Jehoshaphat faces a vast army and wins the battle through prayer and praise, as the Lord fights for Judah. God meets the weary and defends those who trust him.", t: "God spoke to Elijah not in the dramatic but in a still, small voice. How might you quiet your heart enough to hear God whispering to you?" },
  168: { s: "Ahab covets Naboth's vineyard, and Jezebel has the innocent man killed to seize it, bringing God's judgment upon them. In Chronicles, Judah's kings Jehoram and Ahaziah follow the evil ways of Ahab's house, and the kingdom suffers. Greed and injustice never escape the notice of God.", t: "Ahab let envy of what another owned lead to terrible injustice. Where might discontent or coveting be taking root in your own heart?" },
  169: { s: "The prophet Micaiah dares to speak God's true word while all the other prophets flatter the king, and Ahab dies in battle just as foretold. In Chronicles, the priest Jehoiada rescues the boy Joash and restores the rightful king of David's line. God's word stands true even when it is unpopular.", t: "Micaiah spoke God's truth even when everyone around him said the opposite. Where might God be asking you to stand for the truth rather than follow the crowd?" },
  170: { s: "When King Ahaziah seeks a pagan god instead of the Lord, Elijah confronts him and the king dies in his sin. In Chronicles, young King Joash repairs the neglected temple, but later, after his godly mentor dies, he turns away and even kills the prophet who warns him. A good beginning must be matched by lasting faithfulness.", t: "Joash served God well while his mentor lived, but drifted once he was gone. Whose faith strengthens yours, and how can you stay faithful even without their support?" },
  171: { s: "Elijah is taken up to heaven in a whirlwind, and his disciple Elisha receives a double portion of his spirit to carry on the prophetic mission. In Chronicles, King Amaziah of Judah begins well but lets pride and idolatry lead him astray. God's work continues from one generation to the next, but pride can undo even a promising reign.", t: "Elisha longed to carry on Elijah's God-given mission. What good work or faith has been handed to you that God may be asking you to carry forward?" },
  172: { s: "The kings of Israel, Judah, and Edom march against Moab and are saved when Elisha secures water and victory from the Lord. In Chronicles, King Uzziah grows strong and is greatly helped by God, until pride leads him to overstep and he is struck with leprosy. God gives strength, but it must be received with humility.", t: "Uzziah was helped by God until he became proud and forgot his place. When things go well, how do you guard against letting success make you proud?" },
  173: { s: "Elisha works wonders of mercy, multiplying a widow's oil, raising the Shunammite woman's son, and feeding the hungry, showing God's care for ordinary people in need. In Chronicles, King Ahaz of Judah sinks into deep idolatry, even sacrificing his own children. The kindness of God through Elisha shines against the darkness of a faithless king.", t: "Elisha brought God's care into the everyday troubles of ordinary people. Where might God want to use you to bring his compassion into someone's daily need?" },
  174: { s: "The proud Syrian commander Naaman is healed of leprosy only when he humbles himself to wash seven times in the Jordan as the prophet directed. Meanwhile God tells the prophet Hosea to marry the unfaithful Gomer, a living picture of God's faithful love for a wayward people. Healing and love both come through humble trust in God.", t: "Naaman was healed only when he set aside his pride and simply obeyed. Is there a simple thing God is asking of you that your pride finds hard to accept?" },
  175: { s: "Elisha continues to reveal God's power, making an axe head float and striking an enemy army with blindness, and a desperate siege of Samaria is lifted overnight by the Lord. In Hosea, God grieves over Israel's unfaithfulness and empty worship, longing for steadfast love rather than mere sacrifice. God desires hearts that truly know and love him.", t: "God said he desires steadfast love and the knowledge of him more than empty offerings. Is your relationship with God growing in genuine love, or settling into routine?" },
  176: { s: "Elisha foretells suffering for Israel under the cruel Hazael of Syria, and the Shunammite woman's land is restored. In Hosea, God warns that Israel has sown the wind and will reap the whirlwind, for they have forgotten their Maker. Turning from God brings ruin, yet God still calls his people back.", t: "Hosea warned that Israel had forgotten the God who made and loved them. In the busyness of life, how can you keep from forgetting the God who is the source of all you have?" },
  177: { s: "Jehu is anointed to wipe out the wicked house of Ahab, and Jezebel meets her end as God's judgment is carried out. In Hosea, God speaks with tender love: 'When Israel was a child, I loved him,' picturing himself as a father teaching his child to walk. Even amid judgment, God's heart aches with fatherly love for his people.", t: "God remembered teaching Israel to walk as a father holds a child's hands. How does it touch you to know God loves you with that same tender, fatherly care?" },
  178: { s: "Jehu destroys Baal worship in Israel, yet does not fully follow the Lord with all his heart. In Amos, God's word thunders against the surrounding nations and against Israel itself for its injustice and complacency. God sees not only outward religion but how his people treat one another.", t: "Jehu did right outwardly but his heart was not wholly God's. Where might God be inviting your outward actions and your inner heart to come into harmony?" },
  179: { s: "The wicked queen Athaliah is overthrown and the young king Joash is crowned, restoring David's line in Judah. In Amos, God rejects worship that ignores the poor and cries out, 'Let justice roll down like waters, and righteousness like an ever-flowing stream.' True worship of God cannot be separated from justice and mercy.", t: "Amos longed for justice to roll down like a mighty river. Where is God calling you to act more justly and kindly toward those around you?" },
  180: { s: "Elisha dies, but God still gives Israel deliverance, and Jeroboam II restores the nation's borders. In Amos, the prophet sees visions of judgment and the plumb line God holds against his people, yet ends with a promise to one day restore and rebuild. God's warnings are real, but so is his promise of restoration.", t: "God held up a plumb line to measure whether Israel was true and upright. If God measured your life today, where might he be inviting you to straighten and realign?" },
  181: { s: "Israel's kings rise and fall amid intrigue and bloodshed, while Assyria grows in power. Meanwhile God sends the reluctant prophet Jonah to Nineveh; after fleeing and being swallowed by a great fish, Jonah preaches, the city repents, and God spares it, much to Jonah's displeasure. God's mercy reaches even to Israel's enemies.", t: "Jonah resented God's mercy toward people he thought unworthy of it. Is there anyone you find it hard to want God's mercy for, and what might God be teaching you through that?" },
  182: { s: "King Ahaz of Judah turns to Assyria and pagan altars rather than trusting the Lord. In the prophet Micah, God denounces those who scheme against the weak, yet promises a day when nations 'shall beat their swords into plowshares' and walk in the ways of God. Human faithlessness is met by God's promise of lasting peace.", t: "Micah foresaw a day of peace when weapons would become tools for life. Where in your relationships could you trade conflict for peace today?" },
  183: { s: "The northern kingdom of Israel falls to Assyria and its people are carried into exile, the tragic result of generations of unfaithfulness. In Micah, God promises a ruler to come from little Bethlehem and reminds his people what he requires: 'to do justice, and to love kindness, and to walk humbly with your God.' Even in judgment, hope of a coming Savior shines.", t: "Micah summed up the life God desires: do justice, love kindness, walk humbly with him. Which of these three is God inviting you to grow in right now?" },

  // --- Exile ---
  184: { s: "King Hezekiah of Judah trusts the Lord, removes the idols, and stands firm as the mighty Assyrian army threatens Jerusalem. In Chronicles, he reopens and cleanses the temple, restoring the worship that had been neglected. In a dark age, one faithful king turns his people back to God.", t: "Hezekiah's first act was to reopen the door to God's house and restore true worship. Is there a door to God in your own life that needs reopening?" },
  185: { s: "When the Assyrians mock the living God, Hezekiah spreads their threatening letter before the Lord in prayer, and God strikes down the enemy army overnight. In Chronicles, Hezekiah invites all Israel to celebrate a great Passover and return to the Lord. God answers the prayer of those who bring their fears to him.", t: "Hezekiah took his crisis straight to God, laying it out before him in prayer. What threatening situation could you 'spread before the Lord' instead of carrying it alone?" },
  186: { s: "Hezekiah falls gravely ill, and God hears his tearful prayer and grants him fifteen more years, yet pride later leads him to show off his treasures to Babylon. In Chronicles, his faithful reforms and provision for worship are recorded. Even a good king must keep humble before the God who gives him life.", t: "God heard Hezekiah's prayer and gave him more time, yet pride still crept in. How can you receive God's gifts with gratitude rather than letting them feed your pride?" },
  187: { s: "Hezekiah's son Manasseh becomes one of Judah's most wicked kings, filling the land with idolatry and bloodshed. In Chronicles, however, Manasseh is taken captive, humbles himself, and God mercifully restores him, a striking picture of repentance. No one is beyond the reach of God's forgiveness.", t: "Even after great evil, Manasseh humbled himself and God forgave him. Is there a sin you fear is too great for God's mercy, when he longs to forgive you?" },
  188: { s: "The young king Josiah seeks God, and when the lost book of the Law is found in the temple, he tears his robes in grief at how far the people have strayed. In Chronicles, Manasseh's repentance and Josiah's early faithfulness are recounted. The rediscovered word of God awakens a hunger to return to him.", t: "Hearing God's word again broke Josiah's heart and stirred him to change. When was the last time Scripture truly moved you, and how might you listen to it more openly?" },
  189: { s: "Josiah leads a sweeping renewal, destroying the idols, restoring the Passover, and binding the people again to the covenant of the Lord. In Chronicles, the finding of the Law and Josiah's reforms are told in greater detail. One person's faithfulness can spark the renewal of a whole community.", t: "Josiah did not keep his renewed faith to himself but led others back to God. Whom might God want to encourage toward him through your own example?" },
  190: { s: "Despite Josiah's goodness, the long tide of Judah's sin cannot be turned back, and the first deportations to Babylon begin. In Chronicles, Josiah keeps a great Passover but then dies in battle, and the nation declines. The shadow of exile falls as the consequences of generations of unfaithfulness draw near.", t: "Josiah was faithful, yet still carried the weight of others' choices. How can you remain faithful to God even when you cannot fix everything around you?" },
  191: { s: "Jerusalem falls, the temple is destroyed, and the people are carried into exile in Babylon, the lowest point of Israel's story. In Chronicles, the long history is summed up, ending with a glimmer of hope as Cyrus later decrees the people may return. Even in devastation, God does not abandon his promise.", t: "Even as everything was lost, God was already preparing a way home for his people. Where do you need to trust that God is at work even in your darkest season?" },
  192: { s: "The prophet Isaiah opens with God's grief over his rebellious people, yet his tender promise: 'Though your sins are like scarlet, they shall be as white as snow.' He envisions all nations streaming to the mountain of the Lord. In Tobit, we meet a faithful exile who keeps God's law and buries the dead even at great personal cost.", t: "God promised to make scarlet sins as white as snow. What stain do you long for God to wash clean in you?" },
  193: { s: "Isaiah warns that Judah's proud and self-indulgent leaders will be brought low, yet promises a 'branch of the Lord' that will be beautiful and glorious. In Tobit, both the blind Tobit and the grieving Sarah pour out their sorrows in prayer, and God hears them both. God notices the prayers of the suffering and prepares to answer.", t: "God heard the prayers of two suffering people who felt utterly alone. When you feel unheard, can you trust that God is listening and at work?" },
  194: { s: "Isaiah sings of God's vineyard that yielded only wild grapes, then receives his call in the temple, crying 'Holy, holy, holy is the Lord,' and answering, 'Here am I; send me.' In Tobit, the angel Raphael, unrecognized, sets out with young Tobias on a journey of God's hidden providence. God calls and sends those willing to say yes.", t: "Isaiah responded to God's call with, 'Here am I; send me.' Where might God be calling you, and are you willing to make Isaiah's answer your own?" },
  195: { s: "As enemy kings threaten Judah, Isaiah gives the sign of Immanuel: a virgin shall conceive and bear a son, 'God with us.' In Tobit, Tobias marries Sarah, and through prayer the evil that bound her is driven away. Amid fear and darkness, God promises to be present with his people.", t: "Isaiah promised a child to be called 'God with us.' Where do you most need to know that God is with you right now?" },
  196: { s: "Isaiah proclaims the great promise: 'For to us a child is born... and his name shall be called Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.' In Tobit, the old man's sight is restored and the angel Raphael reveals that he was sent by God to heal them. God's promised light breaks into the darkness of his people.", t: "Isaiah named the coming Savior 'Prince of Peace.' What part of your life most needs the peace that only Christ can bring?" },
  197: { s: "Isaiah foresees a shoot springing from the stump of Jesse, a Spirit-filled king under whom the wolf will dwell with the lamb and the earth be full of the knowledge of the Lord. In Tobit, the healed and grateful family praises God, and Tobit's life closes in peace. The promise of a coming kingdom of peace shines through the exile.", t: "Isaiah dreamed of a world filled with the knowledge of the Lord and lasting peace. How can you let that hope shape the way you live and treat others today?" },
  198: { s: "Isaiah declares that proud Babylon and its king will be brought down from their heights. In Joel, a devastating locust plague becomes a call to repentance: 'Return to me with all your heart... rend your hearts and not your garments,' with the promise that God will pour out his Spirit on all people. Genuine repentance opens the way to God's renewing Spirit.", t: "Joel called the people to rend their hearts, not just their garments. Is your turning to God reaching your heart, or only your outward actions?" },
  199: { s: "Isaiah speaks oracles over Moab and Damascus, reminding the nations that no human power endures apart from God. In Joel, God promises to judge the nations and to dwell with and bless his people in Zion. Earthly powers rise and fall, but the Lord remains the refuge of his people.", t: "Joel promised that God himself would be a refuge and stronghold for his people. In a changing and uncertain world, where do you find your security?" },
  200: { s: "Isaiah proclaims God's word over Cush and Egypt, foreseeing a day when even former enemies will worship the Lord. In Nahum, God's justice is pronounced against the violent city of Nineveh. God is patient and merciful, yet he does not ignore cruelty and oppression forever.", t: "Nahum proclaimed that God is good and a refuge, yet also just toward the cruel. How does it comfort you that God both shelters the faithful and will set wrongs right?" },
  201: { s: "Isaiah warns Babylon and rebukes a complacent Jerusalem that feasts when it should mourn and repent. In Nahum, the fall of mighty Nineveh is vividly foretold. Outward security is no safeguard for those who forget God; only humble dependence on him endures.", t: "Jerusalem partied instead of facing what God was saying to it. Where might you be distracting yourself from something God is gently asking you to confront?" },
  202: { s: "Isaiah pronounces judgment on proud Tyre and a coming desolation of the earth. In Habakkuk, the prophet wrestles honestly with God over why evil seems to triumph, and receives the answer that 'the righteous shall live by his faith.' Even in confusion, faith means trusting God's justice and timing.", t: "Habakkuk brought his hardest questions straight to God. What honest question or struggle could you bring openly to God in prayer today?" },
  203: { s: "Isaiah envisions God preparing a feast for all peoples and swallowing up death forever, wiping away every tear. In Habakkuk, the prophet's struggle ends in surrender: 'Though the fig tree does not blossom... yet I will rejoice in the Lord.' Hope in God can hold firm even when everything else fails.", t: "Habakkuk chose to rejoice in God even when his circumstances gave him no reason to. Can you find joy in God himself, apart from what you have or lack?" },
  204: { s: "Isaiah warns the proud leaders of Ephraim and Jerusalem who honor God with their lips while their hearts are far from him, yet promises a sure cornerstone. In Zephaniah, the great and terrible 'day of the Lord' is announced against all complacency. God calls his people from empty religion to a living, humble faith.", t: "God lamented people who honored him with their lips while their hearts were far away. How close is your heart to God in the words you pray?" },
  205: { s: "Isaiah rebukes Judah for running to Egypt for help instead of resting in God, who says, 'In returning and rest you shall be saved.' In Zephaniah, after judgment comes a tender promise: God himself will rejoice over his people with singing. The Lord both corrects his people and delights to restore them.", t: "Zephaniah pictured God rejoicing over his people with gladness and song. How does it move you to imagine that God delights in you?" },
  206: { s: "Isaiah foresees a righteous king and a secure Zion where the Lord himself is their king and judge. In Baruch, the exiles confess their sins honestly and acknowledge that their suffering flows from turning away from God. Honest confession is the first step back toward the God who saves.", t: "The exiles in Baruch owned their sin instead of making excuses. What might God be inviting you to confess honestly before him?" },
  207: { s: "Isaiah proclaims both judgment and the joy of redemption, when 'the desert shall blossom' and God's people return on a holy highway, and recounts God's deliverance of Jerusalem from Assyria. In Baruch, wisdom is found not in human cleverness but in following the commandments God gives. The way home is the path of God's wisdom.", t: "Baruch taught that true wisdom is found in walking in God's ways. Where might real wisdom mean simply doing what God has already shown you?" },
  208: { s: "Isaiah tells how Hezekiah's prayer turned back the Assyrians and how God added years to his life. In Baruch, the exiles are urged to take off their robes of mourning and put on the splendor of God's glory, for he will bring them home; the letter of Jeremiah mocks the powerlessness of idols. God replaces his people's mourning with hope.", t: "Baruch called the people to exchange grief for the hope of God's coming deliverance. What sorrow might God be inviting you to lay down in trust of his future for you?" },
  209: { s: "Isaiah's message turns to comfort: 'Comfort, comfort my people,' a voice cries to prepare the way of the Lord, and those who wait on him 'shall mount up with wings like eagles.' Meanwhile Ezekiel, a priest among the exiles, beholds an overwhelming vision of God's glory by the river Chebar. God comes to comfort and reveal himself even in a foreign land.", t: "Isaiah promised that those who wait on the Lord will renew their strength. Where do you need to wait on God rather than run on your own failing strength?" },
  210: { s: "Isaiah declares, 'Fear not, for I am with you,' and introduces the gentle Servant of the Lord who will bring forth justice. Ezekiel is commissioned as a watchman and told to eat the scroll of God's words, which taste sweet as honey. God's word becomes the prophet's nourishment and his message.", t: "Ezekiel had to take God's word inside himself before he could share it. How might you let Scripture become not just something you read but something you take to heart?" },
  211: { s: "Isaiah proclaims that God has called his people by name and will make a way in the wilderness, exposing the folly of man-made idols. Ezekiel acts out the coming siege of Jerusalem through dramatic signs. God redeems his people while warning them that turning to lifeless idols leads only to ruin.", t: "God told his people, 'I have called you by name, you are mine.' How does it change your day to know that God knows you by name and calls you his own?" },
  212: { s: "Isaiah astonishingly names the pagan king Cyrus as God's instrument to free his people, and declares there is no God besides the Lord. Ezekiel warns that judgment is coming upon Israel's high places, yet a remnant will be spared. God rules over all of history, even using unexpected people to accomplish his purposes.", t: "God worked through an unlikely foreign king to rescue his people. Where might God be working in your life through people or circumstances you would not have chosen?" },
  213: { s: "Isaiah foretells the fall of proud Babylon, whose magic and wisdom cannot save it. In Ezekiel, the prophet is shown the idolatry hidden within the temple itself, and the glory of God begins to depart. Sin grieves God so deeply that his presence will not dwell where he is dishonored.", t: "Ezekiel saw God's glory begin to leave a temple filled with secret sin. Is there a hidden compromise that may be crowding God's presence out of your life?" },
  214: { s: "Isaiah's Servant is appointed 'a light to the nations,' that God's salvation may reach the ends of the earth. In Ezekiel, the glory of the Lord departs the temple, yet God promises to gather his scattered people and give them 'one heart and a new spirit.' Even in exile, God promises inward renewal.", t: "God promised to take away hearts of stone and give hearts of flesh. Where is your heart hard, and how might you ask God to soften and renew it?" },
  215: { s: "Isaiah calls the people to awake and rejoice, announcing, 'How beautiful... are the feet of him who brings good news.' In Ezekiel, God condemns the false prophets who cry 'peace' when there is no peace. God's true word brings real hope, not the false comfort of those who tell people only what they want to hear.", t: "False prophets soothed the people with comforting lies. Are you willing to hear God's truth even when it is harder than the easy words you would prefer?" },

  217: { s: "Isaiah extends God's free invitation: 'Come to the waters... seek the Lord while he may be found,' welcoming even foreigners into God's house of prayer. In Ezekiel, God tells the long story of Jerusalem as an unfaithful bride whom he rescued, loved, and will yet restore. God's mercy reaches beyond what his people deserve.", t: "God invited the thirsty to come freely, without money or price. What keeps you from coming simply and openly to God just as you are?" },
  218: { s: "Isaiah teaches that the fasting God desires is to loose the bonds of injustice and share bread with the hungry. In Ezekiel, God insists that each person is responsible for their own choices and declares, 'I have no pleasure in the death of the wicked,' but longs for them to turn and live. God desires repentance, not ruin.", t: "God said the fasting he wants is to feed the hungry and free the oppressed. How might your devotion to God overflow into concrete care for someone in need?" },
  219: { s: "Isaiah laments that sin has built a wall between the people and God, yet promises light: 'Arise, shine, for your light has come.' In Ezekiel, a sorrowful lament is raised over the fallen princes of Israel. Sin separates, but God still promises the dawning of his light upon his people.", t: "Isaiah declared, 'Arise, shine, for your light has come.' Where do you need to step out of darkness and let God's light shine in your life?" },
  220: { s: "Isaiah proclaims the words Jesus would one day read in Nazareth: 'The Spirit of the Lord God is upon me... to bring good news to the poor,' promising the vindication of Zion. In Ezekiel, God recounts Israel's long history of rebellion and his patient mercy. God anoints his servant to bring good news and refuses to give up on his people.", t: "Isaiah foretold good news for the poor, the brokenhearted, and the captive. Which of these do you most need to hear God's good news for in your own life?" },
  221: { s: "Isaiah pleads with God, recalling his past mercies and crying, 'You are our Father... we are the clay, and you are our potter.' In Ezekiel, the sword of God's judgment is raised against a city full of injustice. The prophet appeals to God as a Father even as judgment looms.", t: "Isaiah called God 'our Father' and the potter who shapes us as clay. Are you willing to let God reshape parts of your life that have grown hard or misshapen?" },
  222: { s: "Isaiah looks ahead to 'new heavens and a new earth,' where God's people will rejoice and sorrow will be no more. In Ezekiel, God exposes the deep unfaithfulness of Jerusalem, and the prophet's own loss of his wife becomes a sign to the people. God's promise of a renewed creation shines even against the backdrop of judgment.", t: "God promised a new creation where weeping and distress would be no more. How does the hope of God's renewed world give you strength for today's sorrows?" },
  223: { s: "Isaiah closes with God's promise to gather all nations to see his glory and create a new and lasting world, while looking with favor on the humble and contrite. In Ezekiel, oracles are pronounced against the nations that gloated over Jerusalem's fall. God treasures the lowly in heart and will set all things right.", t: "God said he looks with favor on the humble and contrite in spirit. How might you cultivate a humble, trembling-before-God reverence in your heart?" },
  224: { s: "God calls the young Jeremiah with the words, 'Before I formed you in the womb I knew you,' appointing him a prophet to the nations despite his fear. In Ezekiel, a haunting lament is raised over the proud merchant city of Tyre. God knows and chooses his servants long before they are ready, and equips them for his work.", t: "God told Jeremiah, 'Before I formed you in the womb I knew you.' How does it change your sense of worth to know God has known and loved you from the very beginning?" },
  225: { s: "Jeremiah accuses Judah of forsaking God, 'the fountain of living waters,' to dig their own broken cisterns that hold no water. In Ezekiel, judgment falls on the proud prince of Tyre, who exalted himself as a god. The deepest tragedy is trading the living God for things that cannot satisfy.", t: "Jeremiah grieved that the people left the fountain of living water for broken cisterns. What 'broken cisterns' are you tempted to depend on instead of God himself?" },
  226: { s: "Jeremiah pleads with faithless Israel to return, promising that God will receive them back with mercy. In Ezekiel, oracles are pronounced against Egypt, on whom Judah had wrongly relied. God's heart is always open to welcome home those who will turn back to him.", t: "God kept calling, 'Return to me,' to a people who had wandered far. Is God gently inviting you to return to him in some area where you have drifted?" },
  227: { s: "Jeremiah warns of disaster sweeping down from the north because of the people's stubborn sin, and weeps over the coming devastation. In Ezekiel, the fall of mighty Egypt is foretold. The prophets grieve, longing for their people to turn back before judgment arrives.", t: "Jeremiah wept over a people who would not listen to God's warnings. Whose well-being weighs on your heart, and how might you bring them to God in prayer?" },
  228: { s: "Jeremiah searches Jerusalem for even one honest person and exposes the corruption running through the city. In Ezekiel, the prophet is appointed a watchman, responsible to warn the people of danger. God looks for faithfulness and calls his servants to speak the truth in love.", t: "Ezekiel was made a watchman, responsible to warn others of danger. Is there a truth God may be asking you to speak lovingly to someone you care about?" },
  229: { s: "Jeremiah announces the siege closing in on a people who refuse to listen. In Ezekiel, God condemns the selfish shepherds who fed themselves instead of the flock, and promises, 'I myself will be the shepherd of my sheep.' Where human leaders fail, God himself promises to care for his people.", t: "God promised to personally shepherd the flock that others had neglected. How does it comfort you to know that God himself watches over you as a caring shepherd?" },
  230: { s: "Jeremiah delivers his temple sermon, warning that the building itself cannot save a people whose lives dishonor God. In Ezekiel, God makes a stunning promise: 'A new heart I will give you, and a new spirit I will put within you.' God wants not just outward religion but transformed hearts.", t: "God promised to give his people a new heart and a new spirit. What part of your heart most needs God's renewing touch today?" },
  231: { s: "Jeremiah grieves over Judah's incurable wound, asking, 'Is there no balm in Gilead?' In Ezekiel, God shows the prophet a valley of dry bones that come to life by his Spirit, a promise that he can raise a dead people to new life. Where all seems hopeless, God breathes life and hope.", t: "God breathed life into a valley of dry, lifeless bones. Is there a part of your life that feels dead, where you need God's reviving Spirit?" },
  232: { s: "Jeremiah weeps day and night over his people's stubbornness and the ruin it will bring. In Ezekiel, God promises to defeat every threatening power and to restore the fortunes of his people. Even amid tears, the prophets hold to God's promise that he will have the final word.", t: "Jeremiah's love for his people moved him to tears, not just words. Whose burdens could you carry to God with that kind of compassion?" },
  233: { s: "Jeremiah contrasts the lifeless idols of the nations with the living God who made the heavens, and laments the broken covenant. In Ezekiel, the prophet is given a vision of a glorious new temple. False gods are powerless, but the true God promises a future where he dwells among his people.", t: "Jeremiah marveled that the living God is utterly unlike any lifeless idol. What lesser things compete for the trust that belongs to the living God alone?" },
  234: { s: "Jeremiah's honest complaints to God and the sign of the ruined linen waistcloth reveal a people who clung to God and then spoiled. In Ezekiel, the heavenly temple is carefully measured, a sign of God's ordered holiness. God invites his prophets to be honest with him even as he points toward a holy future.", t: "Jeremiah brought even his frustrations and questions openly to God. What have you been holding back that you could speak honestly to God in prayer?" },
  235: { s: "Amid drought and rejection, Jeremiah pours out his anguish, yet God assures him he will be a fortified wall against his opponents. In Ezekiel, the glory of the Lord returns to fill the new temple. The faithful servant suffers, but God promises that his presence will dwell with his people again.", t: "God promised the struggling Jeremiah that he would stand by him like a strong wall. Where do you need to trust that God will sustain you through opposition?" },
  236: { s: "Jeremiah declares, 'Blessed is the man who trusts in the Lord,' picturing him as a tree planted by water, while warning against trusting in mere human strength. In Ezekiel, God gives directions for the offerings and feasts of the renewed temple. True flourishing comes from sinking our roots into God.", t: "Jeremiah compared the one who trusts God to a tree planted by streams of water. Where are your roots sunk for security, and how can you root yourself more deeply in God?" },
  237: { s: "Jeremiah watches the potter reshape the marred clay, a sign that God can still remake his people, then dramatizes coming judgment with a broken jar. In Ezekiel, a life-giving river flows from the temple, bringing healing wherever it goes. God is both the potter who reshapes and the source of life-giving renewal.", t: "Ezekiel saw a river from God's house bringing life everywhere it flowed. Where do you long for God's healing, life-giving presence to flow in your life?" },
  238: { s: "Jeremiah is beaten and put in the stocks for speaking God's word, yet cannot keep silent, for it is like 'a fire shut up in my bones.' In Daniel, four young exiles stay faithful to God's ways in Babylon, and Daniel interprets the king's dream of a great statue. Faithfulness to God often costs something, but God honors those who stand firm.", t: "God's word burned in Jeremiah like a fire he could not contain. What truth or conviction has God placed in you that you find hard to keep silent about?" },
  239: { s: "Jeremiah delivers hard words to the unfaithful kings of Judah. In Daniel, three young men refuse to bow to the king's golden statue and are thrown into a blazing furnace, where God walks with them through the fire and they emerge unharmed. God is present with his faithful ones even in their trials.", t: "The three young men trusted God whether or not he rescued them from the fire. Where is God asking you to stay faithful, trusting him with the outcome?" },
  240: { s: "Jeremiah condemns the false shepherds and promises a coming 'righteous Branch' from David's line. In Daniel, proud King Nebuchadnezzar is humbled into madness until he acknowledges God, and later Belshazzar sees the writing on the wall. God lifts up the humble and brings down the proud.", t: "Nebuchadnezzar was humbled until he learned to honor God as the true King. Where might pride be quietly creeping into your life that God invites you to lay down?" },
  241: { s: "Jeremiah's vision of good and bad figs and the prophecy of seventy years frame Judah's exile with hope. In Daniel, the faithful prophet is thrown to the lions for praying to God, but the Lord shuts the lions' mouths and delivers him. God watches over those who remain devoted to him.", t: "Daniel kept praying faithfully even when it could cost him his life. How steady and faithful is your own habit of daily prayer?" },
  242: { s: "Jeremiah faces threats for prophesying against Jerusalem and wears a yoke to picture submission to Babylon. In Daniel, visions of beasts and kingdoms unfold, and Daniel humbly confesses his people's sins and prays for mercy. Earthly empires come and go, but God's kingdom and mercy endure.", t: "Daniel prayed honestly, confessing not only his own sins but his people's. How might you pray not just for yourself but for the needs and failings of those around you?" },
  243: { s: "When the false prophet Hananiah promises a quick end to exile, Jeremiah sends a letter telling the exiles to settle, seek the welfare of the city, and trust God's 'plans... to give you a future and a hope.' In Daniel, further visions reveal the rise and fall of kingdoms under God's hand. God's plans unfold over time and call for patient trust.", t: "God promised plans for a future and a hope, even in the middle of exile. Where do you need to trust God's good plans when life feels like waiting?" },
  244: { s: "Jeremiah proclaims God's promise to restore his people and turn mourning into joy. In Daniel, a vision points to the resurrection of the dead, 'those who sleep... shall awake', and the story of Susanna shows God vindicating the innocent through Daniel's wisdom. God promises both restoration now and the hope of life beyond death.", t: "Daniel glimpsed a day when those who sleep in death will awake to everlasting life. How does the hope of resurrection change the way you face loss and death?" },
  246: { s: "While imprisoned, Jeremiah buys a field as a sign of hope that life will one day return to the land. In Judith, the looming threat of Holofernes' vast army sets the stage for God to deliver his people through unexpected means. Even in confinement and danger, faith dares to invest in God's promised future.", t: "Jeremiah bought a field as an act of hope when all looked lost. What hopeful step could you take that says you trust God with your future?" },
  247: { s: "God invites Jeremiah, 'Call to me and I will answer you,' renewing his promise to heal and restore. In Judith, the Assyrian army besieges the city, and the people's faith is tested to the breaking point. God promises to answer those who call on him, even when deliverance seems impossible.", t: "God said, 'Call to me and I will answer you, and tell you great things.' What would it look like to bring a seemingly impossible situation to God in prayer?" },
  248: { s: "The faithful Rechabites' obedience shames Judah, and King Jehoiakim defiantly burns Jeremiah's scroll, only for God to have it rewritten. In Judith, the besieged town of Bethulia grows desperate and is tempted to give up on God. People may try to silence God's word, but it cannot be destroyed.", t: "A king burned God's word, but it could not be silenced or destroyed. How do you treat God's word, do you let it challenge you, or try to set it aside?" },
  249: { s: "Jeremiah is imprisoned and lowered into a muddy cistern for his unwelcome message, then rescued. In Judith, the courageous widow rebukes the people's despair and pours out a bold prayer before setting out to act. Faith sometimes means trusting God when others have given up hope.", t: "When everyone else despaired, Judith turned first to God in prayer. When those around you lose hope, where do you turn for strength?" },
  250: { s: "Jerusalem falls to Babylon, and Jeremiah, who had warned of this day, is treated kindly and set free. In Judith, the brave widow goes out to the enemy camp, trusting God to work through her. Even as one chapter of God's people ends in sorrow, God preserves and works through the faithful.", t: "Judith stepped out in courage, trusting God to act through her. Where is God inviting you to a courageous step of faith, trusting him with the result?" },
  251: { s: "After Jerusalem's fall, the governor Gedaliah is murdered and the frightened remnant asks Jeremiah to seek God's guidance. In Judith, the widow, by God's strength, strikes down the enemy commander Holofernes and saves her people. God delivers his people in surprising ways and asks them to truly heed his word.", t: "The remnant asked Jeremiah for God's guidance but had already decided not to obey it. Do you seek God's direction genuinely ready to follow it?" },
  252: { s: "Against God's word, the remnant flees to Egypt and slips back into idolatry, and Jeremiah warns them again. In Judith, Israel celebrates its deliverance, and Judith sings a hymn of praise to God their Savior. One people clings to idols, the other lifts grateful praise to the God who saves.", t: "Judith responded to deliverance with a song of wholehearted praise. What has God done for you that deserves your grateful praise today?" },
  253: { s: "God gives a personal word of comfort to Jeremiah's faithful scribe Baruch and pronounces judgment on Egypt. In Lamentations, the prophet weeps over the ruined city of Jerusalem, sitting desolate and abandoned. Grief is given honest voice, even as God remembers his faithful servants.", t: "Lamentations gives words to honest, unhidden grief before God. Is there a sorrow you need to pour out to God rather than carry silently?" },
  254: { s: "Jeremiah proclaims God's word over Philistia and Moab, nations that trusted in their own strength. In Lamentations, the poet pours out anguish over the suffering of Zion under God's hand. The prophets see that no nation, and no person, can stand secure apart from God.", t: "Lamentations dares to bring even confusion and anguish into prayer. How might it help to be completely honest with God about a hard situation?" },
  255: { s: "Jeremiah's oracles continue against the nations and against Babylon itself. At the heart of Lamentations comes a sudden light: 'The steadfast love of the Lord never ceases; his mercies... are new every morning; great is your faithfulness.' Even in the ruins, hope rises from God's unfailing mercy.", t: "In the middle of ruin, the poet found that God's mercies are new every morning. Where do you need to receive God's fresh mercy at the start of this day?" },
  256: { s: "Jeremiah foretells the downfall of Babylon, the empire that destroyed Jerusalem. Lamentations ends with a humble plea: 'Restore us to yourself, O Lord, that we may be restored.' Judgment will come upon the oppressor, and the suffering people turn back to God with hope of restoration.", t: "Lamentations closes by asking God, 'Restore us to yourself.' What part of your relationship with God are you longing for him to restore?" },
  257: { s: "The book of Jeremiah ends by recounting Jerusalem's fall and a glimmer of hope as the exiled king is shown kindness in Babylon. In Obadiah, judgment is pronounced on Edom for gloating over Judah's downfall. God will not forget the cruelty of others, and a faint dawn of hope remains for his people.", t: "Edom was condemned for gloating over another's misfortune. How do you respond when someone who has wronged you suffers, with quiet satisfaction, or with mercy?" },

  // --- Messianic Checkpoint (Matthew) ---
  260: { s: "Jesus heals a leper, a centurion's servant, and many others, showing his authority over sickness, storms, and even demons. He calls the tax collector Matthew to follow him and welcomes sinners to his table. Then he sends out the twelve apostles to proclaim the kingdom, with compassion for crowds who are 'like sheep without a shepherd.'", t: "Jesus looked on the harassed crowds with compassion, seeing their need. Who around you is in need of compassion, and how might you offer it?" },
  261: { s: "Jesus praises John the Baptist, laments the towns that refuse to repent, and gives the tender invitation, 'Come to me, all who labor and are heavy laden, and I will give you rest.' He teaches that he is Lord of the Sabbath and tells parables of the kingdom, the sower, the weeds, the mustard seed, the hidden treasure. The kingdom of God quietly grows and is worth everything.", t: "Jesus invited the weary and burdened to come to him for rest. What burden are you carrying that you could bring to Jesus today?" },
  262: { s: "After John the Baptist is killed, Jesus feeds five thousand, walks on the water, and heals the sick who touch his cloak. He commends the persistent faith of a Canaanite woman, and Peter confesses him as the Christ. On the mountain Jesus is transfigured in glory before his closest disciples.", t: "Peter stepped onto the water but began to sink when he looked at the waves. Where do you need to keep your eyes on Jesus rather than on your fears?" },
  263: { s: "Jesus teaches about welcoming the little ones, forgiving 'seventy times seven,' and the cost of following him. He blesses children, calls the rich young man, and tells the parable of the generous landowner. Then he enters Jerusalem to shouts of 'Hosanna' and cleanses the temple.", t: "Jesus told Peter to forgive not seven times but seventy times seven. Is there someone God is inviting you to forgive again, freely and from the heart?" },
  264: { s: "Jesus answers those who try to trap him, naming the greatest commandments as loving God and loving neighbor. He pronounces woes on hypocrisy that looks holy outside but is empty within, and foretells the end of the age, urging watchfulness. He calls his followers to a faith that is real all the way through.", t: "Jesus warned against looking good on the outside while neglecting the heart. Where might God be inviting your inner life to match your outward faith?" },
  265: { s: "Jesus tells the parables of the ten virgins, the talents, and the final judgment, where the King says, 'As you did it to one of the least of these... you did it to me.' Then a woman anoints him, he shares the Last Supper, and he prays in agony in Gethsemane before his arrest. Love shown to the least is love shown to Christ himself.", t: "Jesus said that whatever we do for the least, we do for him. Who are the 'least of these' in your life through whom you might serve Christ?" },

  // --- Return ---
  267: { s: "King Cyrus of Persia issues a decree allowing the exiles to return to Jerusalem and rebuild the temple, fulfilling God's promise, and the first group journeys home. In Haggai, God stirs the returned people to stop neglecting his house and finish rebuilding it. After long exile, God opens the way home and calls his people to put him first.", t: "Haggai challenged the people for building their own homes while God's house lay in ruins. Where in your life might God be asking to come first again?" },
  268: { s: "The returned exiles rebuild the altar and lay the temple's foundation with joy, though opposition soon halts the work. In Zechariah, God grants visions of hope and cleanses Joshua the high priest, replacing his filthy garments with clean ones. God removes guilt and renews his people for a fresh start.", t: "God exchanged the high priest's filthy garments for clean and festive ones. How does it feel to know God longs to clothe you in his forgiveness?" },
  269: { s: "Encouraged by the prophets, the people resume building and complete the temple, celebrating its dedication with joy. In Zechariah, God declares, 'Not by might, nor by power, but by my Spirit,' and grants further visions of his purposes. God's work is accomplished not by human force but by his Spirit.", t: "God reminded his people that his work is done 'not by might, but by my Spirit.' Where are you relying on your own strength instead of asking for God's Spirit?" },
  270: { s: "The scribe Ezra returns to Jerusalem, devoted to studying and teaching God's law, and leads a group home under God's protecting hand. In Zechariah, God calls for true justice and mercy rather than empty fasting, and promises that Jerusalem will be restored. God seeks worship that flows into justice and kindness.", t: "Ezra set his heart to study, obey, and teach God's law. How might you give more room in your life to learning and living out God's word?" },
  271: { s: "Ezra is heartbroken to find that the people have intermarried with surrounding nations and drifted toward their idols, and he leads them in repentance. In Zechariah comes a bright promise: 'Behold, your king is coming to you... humble and mounted on a donkey,' words fulfilled when Jesus entered Jerusalem. Even amid failure, God points ahead to a humble, coming King.", t: "Zechariah foretold a humble king coming on a donkey, fulfilled in Jesus. What does it mean to you that your King comes in humility rather than worldly power?" },
  272: { s: "Far away in Persia, Nehemiah weeps and prays over Jerusalem's broken walls, then boldly asks the king for permission to go and rebuild. In Zechariah, God promises to pour out a spirit of grace and prayer, and his people will look on 'him whom they have pierced' and mourn. Prayer moves Nehemiah to action, and God promises a future of grace.", t: "Nehemiah prayed earnestly before he ever took action. When you face a big concern, do you bring it to God in prayer before rushing to act?" },
  273: { s: "Nehemiah organizes the people, family by family, to rebuild the wall of Jerusalem, each working on the section near their own home. In Zechariah, God promises a day when 'the Lord will be king over all the earth.' God's great work is accomplished as many people each do their part.", t: "Each family rebuilt the section of wall nearest to them. What is the part right in front of you that God is asking you to take responsibility for?" },
  274: { s: "Despite ridicule and threats, Nehemiah keeps the people building 'with one hand... and a weapon in the other,' and confronts injustice among his own people. Meanwhile, in Esther, a Jewish young woman becomes queen of Persia, quietly placed by God for a purpose not yet revealed. God protects and positions his people even in hostile lands.", t: "Nehemiah pressed on with the work despite mockery and opposition. Where might God be asking you to keep doing what is right even when others discourage you?" },
  275: { s: "Nehemiah finishes the wall in just fifty-two days, and even his enemies recognize that the work was done with God's help. In Esther, the proud official Haman plots to destroy all the Jews, and Mordecai turns to prayer and mourning. Human schemes threaten God's people, but God is quietly at work to save them.", t: "When danger came, Mordecai's first response was to turn to God in prayer and humility. Where do you need to bring a threatening situation honestly before God?" },
  277: { s: "Nehemiah leads the people in a great prayer of confession, retracing God's faithfulness throughout their history and renewing their commitment to him. In Esther, the queen risks her life to approach the king, praying first for God's help, and Haman's evil begins to unravel. Honest remembrance of God's faithfulness fuels courage and trust.", t: "Esther prepared for a frightening moment by first turning to God in prayer. What courageous step do you face that you could first surrender to God?" },
  278: { s: "The people make a solemn covenant to obey God's law, to support his house, and to care for one another. In Esther, the murderous decree is reversed, and the Jews are delivered from destruction. God's people bind themselves to him in gratitude, and God rescues them from danger.", t: "The people committed not to neglect the house and work of God. What concrete commitment might God be inviting you to make to him?" },
  279: { s: "Lots are cast and families volunteer to repopulate the holy city of Jerusalem, settling the rebuilt community. In Esther, the joyful feast of Purim is established to remember God's deliverance for all generations. God's people make their home around his presence and remember his saving acts.", t: "The feast of Purim was set up so God's rescue would never be forgotten. What blessings of God do you want to be sure you remember and celebrate?" },
  280: { s: "The rebuilt wall of Jerusalem is joyfully dedicated with music, thanksgiving, and processions of praise. In Esther, Mordecai is honored, and his earlier dream of deliverance is seen to be fulfilled. The people's labor and trust end in celebration of all God has done.", t: "The people dedicated their finished work to God with overflowing thanksgiving. How might you offer your own accomplishments back to God with gratitude?" },
  281: { s: "Nehemiah makes final reforms, calling the people back to faithfulness in worship, the Sabbath, and their commitments. In Malachi, the last Old Testament prophet, God rebukes half-hearted worship, calls for faithfulness in marriage and giving, and promises to send a messenger to prepare the way of the Lord, with 'Elijah' to come before the great day. The Old Testament closes looking forward to the dawn of the Messiah.", t: "Malachi closes the Old Testament with the promise of a messenger to prepare the Lord's way. As you await God's promises, how can you keep your heart ready and faithful?" },

  // --- Maccabean Revolt ---
  282: { s: "After Alexander the Great, the tyrant Antiochus Epiphanes seizes power, plunders the temple, and forbids the practice of the Jewish faith, even desecrating the altar. Many Jews compromise, but others remain faithful at great cost. In Sirach, the wise teacher opens by declaring that 'all wisdom comes from the Lord' and that the fear of the Lord is its beginning.", t: "Sirach teaches that the fear of the Lord is the beginning of wisdom. How might a deeper reverence for God reshape the choices you make today?" },
  283: { s: "The aged priest Mattathias refuses to abandon God's covenant, sparks the revolt against Antiochus, and charges his sons to be zealous for the law before he dies. In Sirach, the teacher praises wisdom and counsels patience in trials, humility, and faithful friendship. Faithfulness to God may demand courage when the world pressures us to compromise.", t: "Mattathias would not compromise his faith even under deadly pressure. Where are you tempted to bend your convictions to fit in, and how can you stand firm?" },
  284: { s: "Judas Maccabeus takes up the cause, winning unlikely victories against far larger armies as he trusts in God rather than in numbers. In Sirach, the teacher offers practical wisdom about humility, almsgiving, and dealing justly with others. God strengthens those who fight for what is right while leaning on him.", t: "Judas trusted that victory comes from God, not from the size of an army. Where do you face long odds that you need to entrust to God's strength?" },
  285: { s: "After his victories, Judas cleanses and rededicates the desecrated temple, relighting the lamps and restoring worship, the origin of the feast of Hanukkah. In Sirach, the teacher warns against pride and praises humility before God. After darkness and defilement, God's people joyfully restore his worship.", t: "The people rejoiced to cleanse and rededicate what had been defiled. Is there something in your life God is inviting you to cleanse and rededicate to him?" },
  286: { s: "Judas and his brothers rescue scattered Jewish communities surrounded by hostile neighbors, bringing them to safety. In Sirach, the teacher reflects on riches, humility, and the responsible use of free will, that God 'has not commanded anyone to be wicked.' God's people are called to protect one another and to choose good freely.", t: "Sirach reminds us that God leaves the choice between good and evil in our hands. In a decision before you, which path are you choosing, and why?" },
  287: { s: "Antiochus dies in despair after his crimes, and the fighting continues as the faithful defend the temple. In Sirach, the teacher marvels at God's mercy and the wonders of creation, calling people to return to the Lord. Earthly tyrants pass away, but God's mercy and majesty endure.", t: "Sirach calls those who have strayed to turn back to the Lord's mercy. Is God gently inviting you to return to him in some area where you have wandered?" },
  288: { s: "The treacherous general Nicanor threatens the temple, but Judas prays and God grants victory. In Sirach, the teacher gives wise counsel about guarding our speech, avoiding sin, and trusting God. God hears the prayers of his people and helps them in their hour of need.", t: "Sirach warns how much harm careless words can do. How might you bring more care and kindness to the way you speak today?" },
  289: { s: "Judas makes a treaty with Rome, seeking allies in the struggle for freedom. In Sirach, the teacher praises the discipline of the tongue and the value of sincere prayer. God's people use wisdom and prudence even as they trust in him.", t: "Sirach prizes self-control and honest, heartfelt prayer. Where in your life would more self-discipline help you grow closer to God?" },
  290: { s: "The faithful leader Judas Maccabeus falls in battle, mourned deeply by his people, yet the cause endures. In Sirach, the teacher sings the praise of wisdom, which 'came forth from the mouth of the Most High,' and reflects on godly relationships. Even when leaders are lost, God's wisdom and purposes continue.", t: "Sirach pictures wisdom as a gift flowing from the mouth of God. How might you seek and treasure God's wisdom more in your daily life?" },
  291: { s: "Judas' brother Jonathan takes up the leadership and is recognized as high priest amid shifting alliances. In Sirach, the teacher commends integrity, honesty, and a good name. God raises up new leaders to carry on his work, and calls his people to lives of integrity.", t: "Sirach teaches that a good name and integrity are worth more than riches. Where might God be inviting you to greater honesty and integrity?" },
  292: { s: "Jonathan strengthens the nation through diplomacy and continued struggle against Israel's enemies. In Sirach, the teacher urges forgiveness, 'forgive your neighbor the wrong he has done', and generosity in lending to those in need. God's people are called to mercy and open-handed kindness.", t: "Sirach asks how we can expect God's forgiveness while refusing to forgive others. Is there a grudge God is inviting you to release today?" },
  293: { s: "Jonathan forms alliances but is finally captured by treachery. In Sirach, the teacher offers wisdom about health, contentment, and the right use of wealth, noting that 'a cheerful heart' is good for life. God's people learn to hold earthly things loosely and to value what truly matters.", t: "Sirach commends a cheerful and contented heart over anxious striving. What anxieties might you hand to God in exchange for greater peace?" },
  294: { s: "Simon, the last of the brothers, takes the lead and at last wins independence and peace for the people. In Sirach, the teacher reflects on God's ordering of creation and providence over all things. After long struggle, God grants his people a season of rest under his providential care.", t: "Sirach sees God's wise hand ordering all of creation. Where do you need to trust that God is ordering even the details of your life?" },
  295: { s: "Simon's wise and peaceful rule is celebrated, as each person sits 'under his own vine and fig tree' in security. In Sirach, the teacher contrasts empty ritual with true worship that flows from a just and generous heart. God blesses faithful leadership and desires worship joined to righteous living.", t: "Sirach warns that offerings mean little without justice and a sincere heart. How can you make sure your worship of God flows into how you live?" },
  296: { s: "Foreign powers again threaten, but Simon stands firm and the people's freedom is recognized. In Sirach, the teacher offers a prayer for God's deliverance of his people and counsel for living wisely. God's people pray for protection and continue to trust him through every threat.", t: "Sirach models bringing the needs of God's people before him in prayer. Whom might God be calling you to pray for and entrust to his care?" },
  297: { s: "Simon is betrayed and murdered, but his son John Hyrcanus carries on the leadership, and the era of the Maccabees draws toward its close. In Sirach, the teacher honors the work of physicians as part of God's healing and praises the devoted scribe who studies God's law. God's gifts and wisdom are passed on through faithful people in every generation.", t: "Sirach honors the scribe who devotes himself wholeheartedly to God's law. What good work or wisdom is God inviting you to give yourself to faithfully?" },
  298: { s: "Second Maccabees opens with letters urging the Jews of Egypt to keep the feast of the rededicated temple, recalling God's faithfulness. In Sirach, the teacher reflects soberly on life's hardships and the certainty of death. Even amid trials and mortality, God's people remember his mercy and keep faith.", t: "Sirach faces honestly that all of us must one day die. How does keeping eternity in view change the way you live today?" },
  299: { s: "The author explains that he has condensed a longer history so readers may grasp God's saving deeds, recalling how Jeremiah hid the ark. In Sirach, the teacher praises the works of God in creation and begins his famous hymn in praise of faithful ancestors, 'Let us now praise famous men.' Remembering God's deeds and his faithful people strengthens our own faith.", t: "Sirach invites us to remember and give thanks for the faithful who came before us. Whose faith has shaped yours, and how can you thank God for them?" },
  300: { s: "When Heliodorus comes to plunder the temple treasury, God strikes him down, and he is spared only through the high priest's prayer. In Sirach, the teacher praises faithful leaders like Aaron and Phinehas who served God zealously. God defends what is holy and honors those devoted to his service.", t: "The high priest prayed even for the man who had come to rob God's temple. Could you pray for someone who has wronged you, asking God's mercy for them?" },
  301: { s: "Corruption and rivalry over the high priesthood bring trouble upon Jerusalem as some abandon their heritage for foreign ways. In Sirach, the teacher praises David, Solomon, and the prophets, and honors good King Josiah. Faithfulness to God is remembered with honor, while compromise leads to ruin.", t: "Sirach honored those who stayed faithful to God across the generations. What kind of legacy of faith do you hope to leave for those after you?" },
  302: { s: "Antiochus massacres the people and plunders the temple, a dark hour for the faithful. In Sirach, the teacher praises Simon the high priest in his glory and closes with a heartfelt prayer of thanksgiving and a call to seek wisdom. Even in suffering, God's people give thanks and seek his wisdom.", t: "Sirach ends by inviting us to seek wisdom and give thanks to God. What are you most thankful to God for as you reflect today?" },
  303: { s: "The aged scribe Eleazar chooses to be tortured to death rather than betray God's law, leaving a noble example for the young. In Wisdom, the ungodly are shown reasoning that life is short and meaningless, plotting against the righteous one, words that point ahead to Christ. Faithfulness unto death witnesses to a hope the world cannot understand.", t: "Eleazar gave his life rather than betray his faith, even in his old age. What would it mean for you to remain faithful to God whatever the cost?" },
  305: { s: "Judas Maccabeus, trusting in God, wins fresh victories and restores hope to the people. In Wisdom, we are assured that 'the souls of the righteous are in the hand of God,' and rulers are urged to seek wisdom. Though the righteous may suffer now, their future is secure in God.", t: "Wisdom assures us that the souls of the righteous are in God's hand. How does it steady you to know that nothing can snatch you from God's care?" },
  306: { s: "The proud persecutor Antiochus dies a wretched death, acknowledging too late the God he defied. In Wisdom, Solomon tells how he prayed for wisdom and valued her above health, wealth, and beauty. The pursuit of God's wisdom outshines every passing power and possession.", t: "Solomon prized wisdom above riches, health, and beauty. If you could ask God for one gift, what would it be, and why?" },
  307: { s: "The temple is rededicated and the faithful celebrate, even as battles continue. In Wisdom, Solomon prays earnestly for the wisdom that sits beside God's throne, and recalls how wisdom guided God's people from Adam onward. God grants wisdom to those who humbly ask for it.", t: "Solomon admitted he could do nothing rightly without God's wisdom. In what decision do you most need to ask God for his wisdom right now?" },
  308: { s: "After further conflict, peace terms are reached and the people find relief. In Wisdom, we read that God loves all he has made and is merciful to all, 'for your immortal spirit is in all things.' God's power is matched by his patience and love for every creature.", t: "Wisdom says God is merciful because he loves everything he has made. How does it move you that God looks on you, and all people, with such love?" },
  309: { s: "Judas wins a hard battle, and afterward, finding tokens of idolatry on the fallen, he makes atonement and offers prayers and sacrifice for the dead, a passage cherished in the Catholic tradition of praying for the departed. In Wisdom, the folly of idolatry is exposed, worshiping the work of human hands. Love for others reaches even beyond death in prayer.", t: "Judas prayed and made offerings for those who had died. Who among the faithful departed could you remember in your prayers today?" },
  310: { s: "King Antiochus V campaigns against the Jews, but the faithful are preserved and peace is sought. In Wisdom, God's care for his people during the Exodus is recalled, and the emptiness of idols is contrasted with the living God. God watches over his people and shows that he alone is worthy of worship.", t: "Wisdom contrasts lifeless idols with the living God who saves. What lesser things might be quietly taking the place that belongs to God alone?" },
  311: { s: "The deceitful Nicanor again threatens, and the devout Razis gives his life rather than fall into enemy hands. In Wisdom, the terror of the plague of darkness on Egypt is set against the light God gave his people at the first Passover. God is light and salvation to those who trust him, even in their darkest night.", t: "God gave his people light while darkness covered their oppressors. Where do you need God's light to break into a dark or fearful place in your life?" },
  312: { s: "Judas prays, recalling God's past deliverances, and wins a decisive victory over Nicanor, and the people give thanks. In Wisdom, the great hymn on the Exodus celebrates how God protected and provided for his people on their journey. God who saved his people of old is faithful to save still.", t: "Judas drew courage from remembering how God had rescued his people before. What past faithfulness of God can strengthen your trust in him today?" },

  // --- Messianic Fulfillment (Luke) ---
  314: { s: "John the Baptist prepares the way, and Jesus is baptized as the Father's voice declares him the beloved Son. After overcoming temptation in the wilderness, Jesus announces in Nazareth that the Scripture of good news to the poor is fulfilled in him, and he begins to teach, heal, and call his first disciples. The long-awaited Messiah steps into his mission.", t: "Jesus told the fishermen, 'Put out into the deep,' and they caught more than they imagined. Where is Jesus inviting you to trust him and 'put out into deeper water'?" },
  315: { s: "Jesus teaches the Sermon on the Plain, blessing the poor and calling his followers to love their enemies and not to judge. He heals the sick, calms a storm, frees a tormented man, and raises a widow's son and Jairus' daughter. His words and deeds reveal the mercy and power of God's kingdom.", t: "Jesus told his followers to love even their enemies and to be merciful as God is merciful. Who is hard for you to love, and how might you show them mercy?" },
  316: { s: "Jesus feeds five thousand, Peter confesses him as God's Messiah, and Jesus is transfigured in glory before turning resolutely toward Jerusalem. He sends out seventy-two messengers, tells the parable of the Good Samaritan, and gently teaches Martha that one thing is needful. Following Jesus means both active mercy and sitting at his feet to listen.", t: "Jesus told busy Martha that her sister Mary had chosen the better part by listening to him. How can you make space simply to sit and listen to Jesus?" },
  317: { s: "Jesus teaches his disciples to pray with the Our Father and to ask, seek, and knock with confidence. He warns against hypocrisy and greed, urging, 'Do not be anxious,' for the Father knows their needs, and calls them to be watchful and ready. Jesus invites his followers to a life of trusting, prayerful dependence on the Father.", t: "Jesus said not to be anxious, for the Father knows everything you need. What worry could you hand over to your heavenly Father today?" },
  318: { s: "Jesus calls for repentance and tells parables of the kingdom, the mustard seed, the narrow door, the great banquet, and the lost sheep, lost coin, and prodigal son who is welcomed home by a running father. He teaches about true discipleship and the right use of wealth. Above all, he reveals a God who rejoices to welcome sinners home.", t: "The father ran to embrace his prodigal son and threw a feast for his return. Where do you need to trust that God runs to welcome you home, no matter how far you have strayed?" },
  319: { s: "Jesus heals ten lepers, but only one returns to give thanks, and he teaches about the coming of God's kingdom and the need for persistent prayer. He welcomes the humble tax collector's prayer over the proud Pharisee's, blesses children, and calls Zacchaeus down from the tree before entering Jerusalem. Jesus lifts up the humble and grateful heart.", t: "Only one of the ten healed lepers came back to thank Jesus. How readily do you return thanks to God for the good he has done for you?" },
  320: { s: "In Jerusalem Jesus silences those who try to trap him, praises the poor widow's tiny offering, and foretells the days to come. At the Last Supper he gives his body and blood and tells his disciples that he is among them 'as one who serves.' As the cross draws near, Jesus shows that true greatness is found in humble, self-giving love.", t: "Jesus said he was among them as one who serves. Where is Jesus inviting you to find greatness through humble service rather than status?" },

  // --- The Church ---
  322: { s: "Before ascending, the risen Jesus promises the Holy Spirit and tells his apostles they will be his witnesses to the ends of the earth, and Matthias is chosen to replace Judas. In Romans, Paul introduces his gospel: the good news of God's Son, in which God's righteousness is revealed to all who believe. The risen Christ launches his Church and the spread of the gospel.", t: "Jesus told his followers they would be his witnesses to the ends of the earth. In your own corner of the world, how might you witness to him?" },
  324: { s: "Peter heals a man lame from birth in Jesus' name and boldly preaches that salvation is found in him. In Romans, Paul shows that Abraham was justified by faith, and that through Christ we have peace with God, who pours his love into our hearts. Salvation comes as a gift received through faith in Christ.", t: "Paul says that through Christ we have peace with God. How does it change your day to know you are at peace with God through Jesus?" },
  325: { s: "Peter and John are arrested for preaching but boldly proclaim Christ, and the early believers share everything in common. In Romans, Paul teaches that those baptized into Christ have died to sin to walk in newness of life, even amid the ongoing struggle against sin. New life in Christ means both a fresh start and a real battle against sin.", t: "Paul speaks honestly of the struggle to do the good he wants to do. Where do you feel that same struggle, and how can you lean on Christ's help?" },
  327: { s: "The apostles appoint seven deacons to serve, and the Spirit-filled Stephen begins to do great works. In Romans, Paul agonizes over his fellow Israelites and proclaims that 'if you confess with your mouth that Jesus is Lord and believe... you will be saved.' Salvation is offered freely to everyone who calls on the Lord.", t: "Paul says salvation comes to all who confess Jesus as Lord and believe. How might you confess Jesus as Lord more openly in your daily life?" },
  328: { s: "Stephen boldly recounts Israel's history and is martyred, praying for those who stone him as Saul looks on. In Romans, Paul marvels at God's mercy and urges believers to offer their bodies as a living sacrifice and to love sincerely. The first martyr's death and Paul's call both point to lives wholly given to God.", t: "Paul urges us to offer our whole selves to God as a living sacrifice. What would it look like to give God not just an hour but your whole day?" },
  329: { s: "Persecution scatters the believers, who spread the gospel, and Philip baptizes an Ethiopian official searching the Scriptures. In Romans, Paul teaches that love is the fulfilling of the law and calls believers to live honorably and not to judge one another. The good news spreads, and love becomes the mark of those who follow Christ.", t: "Paul says love fulfills the whole law. Whom is God asking you to love more genuinely, perhaps someone you have been quick to judge?" },
  331: { s: "Peter is led to the home of the Gentile Cornelius and realizes that God shows no partiality, opening the gospel to all peoples. In First Corinthians, Paul preaches 'Christ crucified,' the power and wisdom of God that overturns human pride. God welcomes all nations and saves through the seeming foolishness of the cross.", t: "Peter learned that God shows no favoritism among peoples. Is there any group or person you struggle to see as equally loved by God?" },
  332: { s: "At Antioch the believers are first called 'Christians,' and the church grows and shares generously in time of famine. In First Corinthians, Paul reminds a divided church that they are God's field and building, and that their leaders are merely servants of the one foundation, Jesus Christ. Christ alone is the foundation on which the Church is built.", t: "Paul insists that Jesus Christ is the one foundation of our lives. What are you truly building your life upon?" },
  333: { s: "Peter is freed from prison by an angel as the church prays earnestly for him, and the proud King Herod is struck down. In First Corinthians, Paul calls the church to purity and reminds them that their bodies are temples of the Holy Spirit. God hears the prayers of his Church and calls his people to holiness of life.", t: "Paul says your body is a temple of the Holy Spirit. How might that truth shape the way you treat your body and your life?" },
  334: { s: "The Holy Spirit sets apart Barnabas and Saul, and Paul's first missionary journey begins as the gospel spreads to new regions. In First Corinthians, Paul gives guidance on marriage, singleness, and freedom, urging believers to act in love rather than wound a weaker conscience. The gospel goes outward, and love guides how believers use their freedom.", t: "Paul urged believers to let love, not just rights, guide their choices. Where might love call you to give up something you are free to do, for another's sake?" },
  335: { s: "At Lystra Paul is hailed as a god and then stoned, yet he rises and continues preaching. In First Corinthians, Paul gives up his own rights for the sake of the gospel, warns from Israel's example, and points to Christ as the rock that followed them. Following Christ means perseverance and a willingness to set self aside for others.", t: "Paul willingly gave up his rights so that nothing would hinder the gospel. What might God be asking you to set aside for the sake of others' faith?" },
  336: { s: "The Council of Jerusalem decides that Gentiles need not take on the whole law of Moses, opening the Church to all. In First Corinthians, Paul teaches reverence at the Lord's Supper and describes the many spiritual gifts that build up the one body of Christ. The Church is one body with many gifts, united in Christ.", t: "Paul compares the Church to one body with many parts that need each other. What gift has God given you to build up his Church and serve others?" },
  338: { s: "In Athens Paul proclaims the 'unknown god' to be the living Creator who calls all people to repent, pointing to the risen Christ. In First Corinthians, Paul gives the heart of the gospel: Christ died, was buried, and rose again, the firstfruits of those who will rise. The resurrection of Christ is the foundation of Christian hope.", t: "Paul declared that Christ has truly risen, the firstfruits of all who will rise. How does the hope of resurrection shape the way you face death and loss?" },
  339: { s: "In Corinth Paul is encouraged by a vision and stays to teach, joined by Aquila and Priscilla. In First Corinthians, Paul closes by urging the believers to 'let all that you do be done in love.' God strengthens his servants and calls his people to make love the measure of everything they do.", t: "Paul's final charge was to let everything be done in love. Is there an area of your life that needs to be done with more love?" },
  340: { s: "Paul's powerful ministry in Ephesus stirs a riot among those whose idol-trade is threatened. In Second Corinthians, Paul praises God as the Father of mercies who comforts us in affliction so that we can comfort others. God comforts his people in their troubles and equips them to console others.", t: "Paul says God comforts us so that we can comfort others. Who in your life is hurting, and how might you share the comfort God has given you?" },
  341: { s: "Paul bids a tearful farewell to the Ephesian elders, entrusting them to God. In Second Corinthians, Paul describes the glory of the new covenant and declares, 'We walk by faith, not by sight,' calling all to be reconciled to God through Christ. Believers are ambassadors of God's reconciling love in the world.", t: "Paul says we walk by faith, not by sight. Where is God inviting you to trust him even when you cannot yet see the way forward?" },
  342: { s: "Paul is arrested in Jerusalem after returning despite warnings of danger. In Second Corinthians, Paul urges the believers not to be unequally yoked, rejoices over their repentance, and commends generous, joyful giving as a response to God's grace. God's grace moves his people toward holiness and open-handed generosity.", t: "Paul commends giving that flows freely from a grateful heart. How might gratitude for God's grace shape the way you give and share?" },
  343: { s: "Paul makes his defense, recounting how the risen Jesus met him on the road to Damascus. In Second Corinthians, Paul teaches that 'God loves a cheerful giver' and recounts his own sufferings for Christ, boasting only in his weakness. God's strength shines through those who serve him even in hardship.", t: "Paul boasted not in his strengths but in his weaknesses, where God's grace shone. Where might God be at work through a weakness you would rather hide?" },
  344: { s: "A plot against Paul's life is uncovered, and he is sent under guard to Caesarea. In Second Corinthians, Paul tells of his thorn in the flesh and the Lord's answer, 'My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.' God's grace upholds his servants precisely in their limitations.", t: "God told Paul, 'My grace is sufficient for you.' In what weakness or struggle do you need to hear those words from God today?" },

  345: { s: "Paul stands trial before the governor Felix, reasoning about righteousness and the judgment to come. In Galatians, Paul defends the gospel of grace, insisting that we are justified by faith in Christ and not by works of the law. Salvation is God's free gift, received through faith rather than earned.", t: "Paul insists we are made right with God through faith in Christ, not by our own achievements. Where might you be tempted to earn God's love rather than receive it?" },
  346: { s: "Paul appeals to Caesar rather than be handed over to his accusers. In Galatians, Paul proclaims the freedom Christ won for us, warns against falling back into bondage, and describes the fruit of the Spirit: love, joy, peace, patience, and more. Life in the Spirit produces a harvest of love that the law alone never could.", t: "Paul lists the fruit of the Spirit, beginning with love, joy, and peace. Which of these is the Spirit inviting to grow more fully in you?" },
  347: { s: "Paul gives his testimony before King Agrippa, telling how Christ called him to bring light to the nations. In Ephesians, Paul praises the spiritual blessings we have in Christ and declares that we are saved by grace through faith, God's own handiwork created for good works. We are God's masterpiece, saved by grace and made for good.", t: "Paul says we are God's handiwork, created in Christ for good works. What good works might God have prepared specifically for you to do?" },
  348: { s: "Paul, a prisoner, survives a dramatic shipwreck on the way to Rome, trusting God's promise that all aboard will be saved. In Ephesians, Paul calls believers to live in unity, to put on the new self, and to take up 'the whole armor of God.' Through every storm, God's people stand firm clothed in his strength.", t: "Paul tells us to put on the whole armor of God for life's battles. Which piece of God's armor do you most need to take up today?" },
  350: { s: "James teaches that trials produce endurance, that we must be 'doers of the word and not hearers only,' and that genuine faith shows itself in action. In Philippians, Paul counts everything as loss compared to knowing Christ, presses on toward the goal, and urges, 'Rejoice in the Lord always.' Real faith bears fruit, and real joy is found in Christ.", t: "James says faith must show itself in what we do, not only what we say. Where might God be inviting your faith to become visible in action?" },
  351: { s: "James warns about the power of the tongue, calls for humility and patience, and urges believers to pray for one another. In Colossians, Paul exalts Christ as the image of the invisible God in whom all things hold together, and warns against empty human philosophies. Christ is supreme over all, and our words and lives should reflect him.", t: "James says the small tongue can do great good or great harm. How might you use your words today to bless rather than to wound?" },
  352: { s: "Peter encourages believers with a living hope born of Christ's resurrection and calls them to holiness as God's chosen people. In Colossians, Paul urges believers to set their minds on things above and to clothe themselves in compassion, kindness, humility, and love. Those raised to new life in Christ are called to live it out in love.", t: "Peter calls believers to a living hope through Christ's resurrection. How does the hope of eternal life with God change the way you live now?" },
  353: { s: "Peter teaches believers to do good even when they suffer for it, following the example of Christ, and calls leaders to shepherd God's flock willingly. In First Thessalonians, Paul gives thanks for the believers' faith and recalls his gentle, loving care for them like a nursing mother. God's people are called to humble service and tender love for one another.", t: "Peter urges us to do good even when it brings suffering. Where might God be calling you to keep doing what is right despite the cost?" },
  354: { s: "Peter urges believers to grow in faith and virtue and warns against false teachers, looking forward to 'new heavens and a new earth.' In First Thessalonians, Paul comforts believers about those who have died and encourages them to 'pray without ceasing' and give thanks in all circumstances. We live in hope of Christ's return, with hearts turned constantly to God.", t: "Paul encourages us to rejoice always, pray constantly, and give thanks in everything. Which of these three could you grow in today?" },
  355: { s: "John assures believers that if we walk in the light and confess our sins, God faithfully forgives, and he calls us to love one another as God's children. In Second Thessalonians, Paul steadies believers about the day of the Lord and urges them to stand firm and keep working faithfully. Forgiveness, love, and steadfast hope mark the children of God.", t: "John promises that God faithfully forgives the sins we confess to him. Is there something you need to bring honestly to God, trusting his forgiveness?" },
  356: { s: "John proclaims that 'God is love,' and that those who abide in love abide in God, whose perfect love casts out fear. In First Timothy, Paul calls for sound teaching, prayer for all people, and godly, humble leadership in the Church. To know God is to be drawn into his love and to let it shape how we live.", t: "John declares simply that God is love. How might resting in God's perfect love free you from a fear you have been carrying?" },
  357: { s: "John commends walking in truth and love and welcoming fellow workers in the gospel. In First Timothy, Paul urges Timothy to be an example to believers, to pursue godliness with contentment, and to 'fight the good fight of the faith.' A faithful life joins truth and love and presses on in pursuit of God.", t: "Paul told Timothy to fight the good fight of faith and pursue godliness. What is one area where you sense God calling you to keep pressing forward?" },
  358: { s: "Jude urges believers to 'contend for the faith' against those who distort God's grace, and closes by praising God who is able to keep us from falling. In Second Timothy, Paul, nearing the end, charges Timothy to guard the faith and to endure hardship as a good soldier of Christ. We are called to hold fast to the faith and entrust ourselves to the God who keeps us.", t: "Jude praises the God who is able to keep you from falling. Where do you need to lean on God's power rather than your own to stand firm?" },
  359: { s: "John sees the glorified Christ among the lampstands and records his words to seven churches, calling them to repentance and faithfulness. In Second Timothy, Paul gives his final charge: 'Preach the word,' and looks ahead to the crown of righteousness, having 'fought the good fight' and 'kept the faith.' Christ calls his Church to faithfulness to the very end.", t: "Paul could say at the end, 'I have kept the faith.' What would help you remain faithful to God all the way to the end of your life?" },
  360: { s: "John is caught up to see the throne of heaven, where all creation worships God and the Lamb who was slain, and a great multitude from every nation stands before him. In Titus, Paul calls for sound teaching and lives transformed by the grace of God that brings salvation. Heaven's worship draws every people, and grace forms a people eager to do good.", t: "John saw a worshiping multitude from every nation before God's throne. How does it inspire you to know your worship joins that of heaven itself?" },
  361: { s: "As John's vision unfolds, trumpets sound and two faithful witnesses testify amid judgment, yet heaven declares that 'the kingdom of the world has become the kingdom of our Lord.' In Philemon, Paul gently appeals for the runaway slave Onesimus to be welcomed back as a beloved brother. God's kingdom triumphs, and the gospel transforms even our relationships into bonds of love.", t: "Paul asked Philemon to receive Onesimus no longer as a slave but as a brother. How might the gospel reshape a relationship in your life into something more loving?" },
  363: { s: "John sees the final plagues and the fall of 'Babylon,' the symbol of every power that defies God. In Hebrews, Christ is shown as our great high priest in the order of Melchizedek, the mediator of a new and better covenant who saves completely those who come to God through him. Christ our high priest brings us near to God forever.", t: "Hebrews says Jesus always lives to intercede for those who come to God through him. How does it comfort you that Christ himself is praying for you?" },
  364: { s: "John sees the final fall of 'Babylon,' the defeat of evil, and the last judgment before the throne of God. In Hebrews, we learn that Christ offered himself once for all to take away sin, and we are urged to draw near to God with confidence and to spur one another on in love. Christ's one perfect sacrifice opens the way for us to approach God with assurance.", t: "Hebrews invites us to draw near to God with confidence because of Christ. What holds you back from approaching God boldly, and how might Christ free you from it?" },

  // ENTRIES
};
